{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780728407859,"sessionID":"ses_164517a81ffemKHCVyXGgLqE5C","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_yGUhi1QOQmIAUZCrQL9vL4BE","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"Performance|Rate limiting|rate limiting|latency|Token savings|token efficiency","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md","include":"README.md"},"output":"Found 13 matches\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md:\n  Line 18:   <a href=\"#performance\">Performance</a> &middot;\n\n  Line 36: **Built for fleets, not single agents.** Public agent-memory benchmarks (LoCoMo, LongMemEval) measure one agent, one user, one long conversation — the single-chatbot shape. The deployment shape we see in production is the opposite: dozens or thousands of agents working on behalf of a company, sharing what they learn under governance. MemClaw is architected around that shape from day one — scoped memory, cross-agent outcome propagation, fleet-wide trust tiers — and competes on the axes that compound with agent count: latency, token efficiency, and governance. See [Performance](#performance) for the numbers, or read the [benchmarks write-up](https://memclaw.net/blog/memclaw-benchmarks).\n\n  Line 279: ## Performance\n\n  Line 283: |  | LoCoMo | LongMemEval | Search latency |\n\n  Line 286: | Token savings vs full context | **96.6%** | **98.2%** | — |\n\n  Line 289: Accuracy sits inside the leading cluster across the field (Mem0, Zep, MemClaw — scores cluster in a narrow band). The axes we push hardest are latency and token efficiency, because those are the ones that compound as agent count grows — a few hundred ms of search latency disappears behind one LLM call, but bills millions of times a day across a fleet.\n\n  Line 693: **Rate limiting (managed platform)**\n\n  Line 695: These limits apply to the managed platform at `memclaw.net`. In the OSS edition, rate limiting is a no-op — see the [Rate limiting](#rate-limiting) section below.\n\n  Line 802: Write latency is dominated by LLM enrichment. Recall latency by the embedding API call.\n\n  Line 805: python scripts/latency_test.py --url http://localhost:8000 --api-key <admin-key> --runs 20\n\n  Line 932: ## Rate limiting\n\n  Line 934: Rate limiting in the OSS edition is a **no-op** — all rate-limit decorators are identity\n\n  Line 936: the internet, add rate limiting at your reverse proxy (nginx, Caddy, Cloudflare) or implement\n","metadata":{"matches":13,"truncated":false},"title":"Performance|Rate limiting|rate limiting|latency|Token savings|token efficiency","time":{"start":1780728407853,"end":1780728407859}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_08894dee5e4995e6016a23c257bd788191aff9fc92146c054f"}},"id":"prt_e9baf2724001WcnskPDT8NqbZS","sessionID":"ses_164517a81ffemKHCVyXGgLqE5C","messageID":"msg_e9baef9a40011Az8aNRFH08ziT"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780728407863,"sessionID":"ses_164517a81ffemKHCVyXGgLqE5C","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_cmFyqcfssDZuyfSho8oU3uAg","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/common/embedding/_service.py","offset":235,"limit":90},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/common/embedding/_service.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n235: async def get_embedding(\n236:     text: str, tenant_config: object | None = None\n237: ) -> list[float] | None:\n238:     \"\"\"Generate an embedding with retry. Returns ``None`` on exhausted retries.\n239: \n240:     Caller-friendly degradation: a transient OpenAI/Vertex hiccup\n241:     returns ``None`` rather than raising, so write paths can persist\n242:     rows with ``embedding=NULL`` and let the async-embed worker backfill.\n243:     The same ``None`` is returned on a registry-level\n244:     ``ValueError`` (env-var misconfiguration) — see\n245:     :func:`_resolve_provider_or_degrade`.\n246: \n247:     This is the document/ingest path. For search-side queries that should\n248:     pass through an instruction-aware encoder (Qwen3-Embedding, e5-instruct,\n249:     etc.), use :func:`get_query_embedding` instead.\n250:     \"\"\"\n251:     provider = await _resolve_provider_or_degrade(tenant_config, \"Embedding\")\n252:     if provider is None:\n253:         return None\n254:     return await _run_with_retry(lambda: provider.embed(text), \"Embedding\")\n255: \n256: \n257: async def get_query_embedding(\n258:     text: str,\n259:     tenant_config: object | None = None,\n260:     instruction: str | None = None,\n261: ) -> list[float] | None:\n262:     \"\"\"Generate a query-side embedding (instruction-aware, asymmetric).\n263: \n264:     For instruction-aware models (Qwen3-Embedding, e5-instruct, KaLM), the\n265:     query encoder expects a task-description prefix that documents do not\n266:     receive. Symmetric providers (OpenAI ``text-embedding-3-small``,\n267:     ``bge-m3``, ``gte-en-v1.5``, ``Fake``, ``Local``, ``Vertex``) do not\n268:     implement :class:`~common.embedding.protocols.InstructionAwareEmbedder`\n269:     — the call site below detects that and falls back to the symmetric\n270:     :meth:`embed` path, matching :func:`get_embedding`.\n271: \n272:     Same retry / degradation semantics as :func:`get_embedding`: returns\n273:     ``None`` after exhausted retries rather than raising, so search routes\n274:     can degrade gracefully (typically by raising 503 to the caller). The\n275:     same ``None`` is returned on a registry-level ``ValueError`` (env-var\n276:     misconfiguration).\n277:     \"\"\"\n278:     provider = await _resolve_provider_or_degrade(tenant_config, \"Query embedding\")\n279:     if provider is None:\n280:         return None\n281: \n282:     # ``InstructionAwareEmbedder`` is an optional ``@runtime_checkable``\n283:     # Protocol declared in ``common.embedding.protocols`` for exactly\n284:     # this dispatch. Only providers backed by an instruction-aware\n285:     # model (e.g. ``OpenAIEmbeddingProvider`` pointed at\n286:     # Qwen3-Embedding) conform. ``Fake`` / ``Local`` / ``Vertex`` do\n287:     # not implement ``embed_query`` and the isinstance check returns\n288:     # False — they fall through to :meth:`embed` and silently ignore\n289:     # *instruction*.\n290:     is_instruction_aware = isinstance(provider, InstructionAwareEmbedder)\n291: \n292:     async def _call() -> list[float]:\n293:         # Inner ``def`` rather than a ``lambda`` so the closure captures\n294:         # *provider* / *text* / *instruction* with explicit ``await``\n295:         # ergonomics; ruff E731 disapproves of ``make_call = lambda:``.\n296:         if is_instruction_aware:\n297:             return await provider.embed_query(text, instruction)\n298:         return await provider.embed(text)\n299: \n300:     return await _run_with_retry(_call, \"Query embedding\")\n\n(End of file - total 300 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"async def get_embedding(\n    text: str, tenant_config: object | None = None\n) -> list[float] | None:\n    \"\"\"Generate an embedding with retry. Returns ``None`` on exhausted retries.\n\n    Caller-friendly degradation: a transient OpenAI/Vertex hiccup\n    returns ``None`` rather than raising, so write paths can persist\n    rows with ``embedding=NULL`` and let the async-embed worker backfill.\n    The same ``None`` is returned on a registry-level\n    ``ValueError`` (env-var misconfiguration) — see\n    :func:`_resolve_provider_or_degrade`.\n\n    This is the document/ingest path. For search-side queries that should\n    pass through an instruction-aware encoder (Qwen3-Embedding, e5-instruct,\n    etc.), use :func:`get_query_embedding` instead.\n    \"\"\"\n    provider = await _resolve_provider_or_degrade(tenant_config, \"Embedding\")\n    if provider is None:\n        return None\n    return await _run_with_retry(lambda: provider.embed(text), \"Embedding\")","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/common/embedding/_service.py","text":"async def get_embedding(\n    text: str, tenant_config: object | None = None\n) -> list[float] | None:\n    \"\"\"Generate an embedding with retry. Returns ``None`` on exhausted retries.\n\n    Caller-friendly degradation: a transient OpenAI/Vertex hiccup\n    returns ``None`` rather than raising, so write paths can persist\n    rows with ``embedding=NULL`` and let the async-embed worker backfill.\n    The same ``None`` is returned on a registry-level\n    ``ValueError`` (env-var misconfiguration) — see\n    :func:`_resolve_provider_or_degrade`.\n\n    This is the document/ingest path. For search-side queries that should\n    pass through an instruction-aware encoder (Qwen3-Embedding, e5-instruct,\n    etc.), use :func:`get_query_embedding` instead.\n    \"\"\"\n    provider = await _resolve_provider_or_degrade(tenant_config, \"Embedding\")\n    if provider is None:\n        return None\n    return await _run_with_retry(lambda: provider.embed(text), \"Embedding\")\n\n\nasync def get_query_embedding(\n    text: str,\n    tenant_config: object | None = None,\n    instruction: str | None = None,\n) -> list[float] | None:\n    \"\"\"Generate a query-side embedding (instruction-aware, asymmetric).\n\n    For instruction-aware models (Qwen3-Embedding, e5-instruct, KaLM), the\n    query encoder expects a task-description prefix that documents do not\n    receive. Symmetric providers (OpenAI ``text-embedding-3-small``,\n    ``bge-m3``, ``gte-en-v1.5``, ``Fake``, ``Local``, ``Vertex``) do not\n    implement :class:`~common.embedding.protocols.InstructionAwareEmbedder`\n    — the call site below detects that and falls back to the symmetric\n    :meth:`embed` path, matching :func:`get_embedding`.\n\n    Same retry / degradation semantics as :func:`get_embedding`: returns\n    ``None`` after exhausted retries rather than raising, so search routes\n    can degrade gracefully (typically by raising 503 to the caller). The\n    same ``None`` is returned on a registry-level ``ValueError`` (env-var\n    misconfiguration).\n    \"\"\"\n    provider = await _resolve_provider_or_degrade(tenant_config, \"Query embedding\")\n    if provider is None:\n        return None\n\n    # ``InstructionAwareEmbedder`` is an optional ``@runtime_checkable``\n    # Protocol declared in ``common.embedding.protocols`` for exactly\n    # this dispatch. Only providers backed by an instruction-aware\n    # model (e.g. ``OpenAIEmbeddingProvider`` pointed at\n    # Qwen3-Embedding) conform. ``Fake`` / ``Local`` / ``Vertex`` do\n    # not implement ``embed_query`` and the isinstance check returns\n    # False — they fall through to :meth:`embed` and silently ignore\n    # *instruction*.\n    is_instruction_aware = isinstance(provider, InstructionAwareEmbedder)\n\n    async def _call() -> list[float]:\n        # Inner ``def`` rather than a ``lambda`` so the closure captures\n        # *provider* / *text* / *instruction* with explicit ``await``\n        # ergonomics; ruff E731 disapproves of ``make_call = lambda:``.\n        if is_instruction_aware:\n            return await provider.embed_query(text, instruction)\n        return await provider.embed(text)\n\n    return await _run_with_retry(_call, \"Query embedding\")","lineStart":235,"lineEnd":300,"totalLines":300,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/common/embedding/_service.py","time":{"start":1780728407860,"end":1780728407863}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_08894dee5e4995e6016a23c257bd808191a4f0e5f3029fe7f6"}},"id":"prt_e9baf272e001NVQac8r2p9GDpV","sessionID":"ses_164517a81ffemKHCVyXGgLqE5C","messageID":"msg_e9baef9a40011Az8aNRFH08ziT"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1780728408193,"sessionID":"ses_164517a81ffemKHCVyXGgLqE5C","part":{"id":"prt_e9baf287f0019SVFe5Y0T6EIt0","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"274fb7c808f944b1c11e7324db9d0504adcc1dff","messageID":"msg_e9baef9a40011Az8aNRFH08ziT","sessionID":"ses_164517a81ffemKHCVyXGgLqE5C","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":41119,"input":9850,"output":531,"reasoning":18,"cache":{"write":0,"read":30720}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1780728413611,"sessionID":"ses_164517a81ffemKHCVyXGgLqE5C","part":{"id":"prt_e9baf3daa001kjMnG1Swkst6Po","messageID":"msg_e9baf2985001z0btwIoqxLOoa9","sessionID":"ses_164517a81ffemKHCVyXGgLqE5C","snapshot":"268dfca7d61a120b6cbd8df985d916c9831a0361","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780728478428,"sessionID":"ses_164517a81ffemKHCVyXGgLqE5C","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_aE8ZUeJGjm5mhhz5mCAZBg21","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md","offset":279,"limit":80},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n279: ## Performance\n280: \n281: Benchmarked against the two most-cited public agent-memory benchmarks. Methodology and operator-scale context live in [`docs/performance.md`](docs/performance.md); the full write-up is on the blog.\n282: \n283: |  | LoCoMo | LongMemEval | Search latency |\n284: |---|---|---|---|\n285: | Accuracy (LLM-judge) | **77.6%** | **72.5%** | — |\n286: | Token savings vs full context | **96.6%** | **98.2%** | — |\n287: | Latency | — | — | **23 ms p50 · 27 ms p95** |\n288: \n289: Accuracy sits inside the leading cluster across the field (Mem0, Zep, MemClaw — scores cluster in a narrow band). The axes we push hardest are latency and token efficiency, because those are the ones that compound as agent count grows — a few hundred ms of search latency disappears behind one LLM call, but bills millions of times a day across a fleet.\n290: \n291: > Single-agent benchmarks can't measure cross-agent recall, outcome propagation between agents, fleet-scoped visibility, or governance-aware retrieval. Those are the questions that decide whether a memory system is *deployable* inside a company. See [`docs/performance.md`](docs/performance.md#what-these-benchmarks-cant-measure).\n292: \n293: Source: [Fast, Token-Efficient, and Built for Fleets](https://memclaw.net/blog/memclaw-benchmarks) (2026-04-19).\n294: \n295: ---\n296: \n297: ## MCP (Model Context Protocol)\n298: \n299: Add MemClaw to any MCP client with one config block.\n300: \n301: **Self-hosted** (localhost):\n302: \n303: ```json\n304: {\n305:   \"mcpServers\": {\n306:     \"memclaw\": {\n307:       \"url\": \"http://localhost:8000/mcp\",\n308:       \"headers\": { \"X-API-Key\": \"standalone\" }\n309:     }\n310:   }\n311: }\n312: ```\n313: \n314: **Managed platform** (memclaw.net):\n315: \n316: ```json\n317: {\n318:   \"mcpServers\": {\n319:     \"memclaw\": {\n320:       \"url\": \"https://memclaw.net/mcp\",\n321:       \"headers\": { \"X-API-Key\": \"mc_your_api_key_here\" }\n322:     }\n323:   }\n324: }\n325: ```\n326: \n327: > For team or production use, swap the tenant-scoped key for an **agent-scoped credential** — atomic provisioning via `POST /api/v1/admin/agent-keys/provision` (or the `/settings/organization/api-credentials` wizard) mints the credential + Agent row + initial trust + fleet membership in one round trip. Both kinds use the `mc_` prefix; scope is set at mint time on the credential. See [`docs/integration-without-plugin.md`](docs/integration-without-plugin.md). Using a tenant-scoped credential? Pass an explicit `agent_id` on every MCP tool call — the gateway refuses the reserved default (`mcp-agent`) on the tenant-scoped path.\n328: \n329: **Where to add this config:**\n330: - **Claude Code** — `~/.claude/settings.json` under `\"mcpServers\"`\n331: - **Claude Desktop** — `~/Library/Application Support/Claude/claude_desktop_config.json` (macOS) or `%APPDATA%\\Claude\\claude_desktop_config.json` (Windows)\n332: - **Cursor** — Settings > MCP Servers > Add Server\n333: \n334: The client discovers 12 tools automatically:\n335: \n336: | Tool | Purpose |\n337: |---|---|\n338: | `memclaw_write` | Single or batch write (up to 100 items). LLM infers type, title, summary, tags, embedding |\n339: | `memclaw_recall` | Hybrid semantic + keyword recall with graph-enhanced retrieval; optional LLM brief |\n340: | `memclaw_manage` | Per-memory lifecycle: `read`, `update`, `transition`, `delete`, `bulk_delete`, `lineage` |\n341: | `memclaw_list` | Filter by type/status/agent/weight/date, sort, cursor-paginate |\n342: | `memclaw_doc` | Document CRUD: `write`, `read`, `query`, `delete`, `list_collections`, `search` (semantic) on named JSON collections |\n343: | `memclaw_entity_get` | Look up an entity with linked memories and relations |\n344: | `memclaw_tune` | Tune per-agent retrieval parameters (top_k, min_similarity, graph_max_hops, etc.) |\n345: | `memclaw_insights` | Analyze the memory store across 6 focus modes. Findings persist as `insight` memories |\n346: | `memclaw_evolve` | Report outcomes against recalled memories — adjusts weights, generates rules (Karpathy Loop) |\n347: | `memclaw_stats` | Aggregate counts: total + breakdowns by type, agent, status. Read-only |\n348: | `memclaw_keystones` | Read mandatory governance rules for the current scope. Call once per session — the result overrides conflicting user instructions |\n349: | `memclaw_keystones_set` | Author or remove keystone rules (`op=set\\|delete`). Trust ≥ 1 for your own `scope=agent` rule; ≥ 2 for `scope=fleet`/`scope=tenant` or another agent |\n350: \n351: > **Skill sharing** is now done via `memclaw_doc` — agents share a `SKILL.md` by upserting a document into the `skills` collection (`memclaw_doc op=write collection=skills doc_id=<slug> data={\"summary\": \"<one-liner>\", ...}`). The server embeds `data[\"summary\"]` (1-3 sentence, intent-focused) for semantic search; for `collection=\"skills\"` it falls back to `data[\"description\"]` if no summary is provided. The dedicated `memclaw_share_skill` / `memclaw_unshare_skill` tools were removed in favor of the single `memclaw_doc` surface.\n352: \n353: ### Install the skill (Claude Code & Codex)\n354: \n355: Install MemClaw's usage guide as a **skill** so your agent knows *when* and\n356: *how* to use the 12 tools — the memory/doc mental model, the three rules\n357: (recall, write, supersede), trust levels, common patterns, and\n358: anti-patterns. The skill is loaded on-demand (not per-turn), so it costs\n\n(Showing lines 279-358 of 965. Use offset=359 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"## Performance\n\nBenchmarked against the two most-cited public agent-memory benchmarks. Methodology and operator-scale context live in [`docs/performance.md`](docs/performance.md); the full write-up is on the blog.\n\n|  | LoCoMo | LongMemEval | Search latency |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Accuracy (LLM-judge) | **77.6%** | **72.5%** | — |\n| Token savings vs full context | **96.6%** | **98.2%** | — |\n| Latency | — | — | **23 ms p50 · 27 ms p95** |\n\nAccuracy sits inside the leading cluster across the field (Mem0, Zep, MemClaw — scores cluster in a narrow band). The axes we push hardest are latency and token efficiency, because those are the ones that compound as agent count grows — a few hundred ms of search latency disappears behind one LLM call, but bills millions of times a day across a fleet.\n\n> Single-agent benchmarks can't measure cross-agent recall, outcome propagation between agents, fleet-scoped visibility, or governance-aware retrieval. Those are the questions that decide whether a memory system is *deployable* inside a company. See [`docs/performance.md`](docs/performance.md#what-these-benchmarks-cant-measure).\n\nSource: [Fast, Token-Efficient, and Built for Fleets](https://memclaw.net/blog/memclaw-benchmarks) (2026-04-19).\n\n---\n\n## MCP (Model Context Protocol)\n","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md","text":"## Performance\n\nBenchmarked against the two most-cited public agent-memory benchmarks. Methodology and operator-scale context live in [`docs/performance.md`](docs/performance.md); the full write-up is on the blog.\n\n|  | LoCoMo | LongMemEval | Search latency |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Accuracy (LLM-judge) | **77.6%** | **72.5%** | — |\n| Token savings vs full context | **96.6%** | **98.2%** | — |\n| Latency | — | — | **23 ms p50 · 27 ms p95** |\n\nAccuracy sits inside the leading cluster across the field (Mem0, Zep, MemClaw — scores cluster in a narrow band). The axes we push hardest are latency and token efficiency, because those are the ones that compound as agent count grows — a few hundred ms of search latency disappears behind one LLM call, but bills millions of times a day across a fleet.\n\n> Single-agent benchmarks can't measure cross-agent recall, outcome propagation between agents, fleet-scoped visibility, or governance-aware retrieval. Those are the questions that decide whether a memory system is *deployable* inside a company. See [`docs/performance.md`](docs/performance.md#what-these-benchmarks-cant-measure).\n\nSource: [Fast, Token-Efficient, and Built for Fleets](https://memclaw.net/blog/memclaw-benchmarks) (2026-04-19).\n\n---\n\n## MCP (Model Context Protocol)\n\nAdd MemClaw to any MCP client with one config block.\n\n**Self-hosted** (localhost):\n\n```json\n{\n  \"mcpServers\": {\n    \"memclaw\": {\n      \"url\": \"http://localhost:8000/mcp\",\n      \"headers\": { \"X-API-Key\": \"standalone\" }\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Managed platform** (memclaw.net):\n\n```json\n{\n  \"mcpServers\": {\n    \"memclaw\": {\n      \"url\": \"https://memclaw.net/mcp\",\n      \"headers\": { \"X-API-Key\": \"mc_your_api_key_here\" }\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n> For team or production use, swap the tenant-scoped key for an **agent-scoped credential** — atomic provisioning via `POST /api/v1/admin/agent-keys/provision` (or the `/settings/organization/api-credentials` wizard) mints the credential + Agent row + initial trust + fleet membership in one round trip. Both kinds use the `mc_` prefix; scope is set at mint time on the credential. See [`docs/integration-without-plugin.md`](docs/integration-without-plugin.md). Using a tenant-scoped credential? Pass an explicit `agent_id` on every MCP tool call — the gateway refuses the reserved default (`mcp-agent`) on the tenant-scoped path.\n\n**Where to add this config:**\n- **Claude Code** — `~/.claude/settings.json` under `\"mcpServers\"`\n- **Claude Desktop** — `~/Library/Application Support/Claude/claude_desktop_config.json` (macOS) or `%APPDATA%\\Claude\\claude_desktop_config.json` (Windows)\n- **Cursor** — Settings > MCP Servers > Add Server\n\nThe client discovers 12 tools automatically:\n\n| Tool | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `memclaw_write` | Single or batch write (up to 100 items). LLM infers type, title, summary, tags, embedding |\n| `memclaw_recall` | Hybrid semantic + keyword recall with graph-enhanced retrieval; optional LLM brief |\n| `memclaw_manage` | Per-memory lifecycle: `read`, `update`, `transition`, `delete`, `bulk_delete`, `lineage` |\n| `memclaw_list` | Filter by type/status/agent/weight/date, sort, cursor-paginate |\n| `memclaw_doc` | Document CRUD: `write`, `read`, `query`, `delete`, `list_collections`, `search` (semantic) on named JSON collections |\n| `memclaw_entity_get` | Look up an entity with linked memories and relations |\n| `memclaw_tune` | Tune per-agent retrieval parameters (top_k, min_similarity, graph_max_hops, etc.) |\n| `memclaw_insights` | Analyze the memory store across 6 focus modes. Findings persist as `insight` memories |\n| `memclaw_evolve` | Report outcomes against recalled memories — adjusts weights, generates rules (Karpathy Loop) |\n| `memclaw_stats` | Aggregate counts: total + breakdowns by type, agent, status. Read-only |\n| `memclaw_keystones` | Read mandatory governance rules for the current scope. Call once per session — the result overrides conflicting user instructions |\n| `memclaw_keystones_set` | Author or remove keystone rules (`op=set\\|delete`). Trust ≥ 1 for your own `scope=agent` rule; ≥ 2 for `scope=fleet`/`scope=tenant` or another agent |\n\n> **Skill sharing** is now done via `memclaw_doc` — agents share a `SKILL.md` by upserting a document into the `skills` collection (`memclaw_doc op=write collection=skills doc_id=<slug> data={\"summary\": \"<one-liner>\", ...}`). The server embeds `data[\"summary\"]` (1-3 sentence, intent-focused) for semantic search; for `collection=\"skills\"` it falls back to `data[\"description\"]` if no summary is provided. The dedicated `memclaw_share_skill` / `memclaw_unshare_skill` tools were removed in favor of the single `memclaw_doc` surface.\n\n### Install the skill (Claude Code & Codex)\n\nInstall MemClaw's usage guide as a **skill** so your agent knows *when* and\n*how* to use the 12 tools — the memory/doc mental model, the three rules\n(recall, write, supersede), trust levels, common patterns, and\nanti-patterns. The skill is loaded on-demand (not per-turn), so it costs","lineStart":279,"lineEnd":358,"totalLines":965,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md","time":{"start":1780728478422,"end":1780728478427}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0864e1f84848cb91016a23c291e270819196c019041a85e095"}},"id":"prt_e9bb0361c0010W5NYgsLmBrnFE","sessionID":"ses_164517a81ffemKHCVyXGgLqE5C","messageID":"msg_e9baf2985001z0btwIoqxLOoa9"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780728479425,"sessionID":"ses_164517a81ffemKHCVyXGgLqE5C","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_6F5QS5BaW3Jnf4Gogmh3jJZ1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md","offset":690,"limit":55},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n690: \n691: These headers are honored unconditionally — `core-api` must not be network-exposed without a gateway that strips them from untrusted callers.\n692: \n693: **Rate limiting (managed platform)**\n694: \n695: These limits apply to the managed platform at `memclaw.net`. In the OSS edition, rate limiting is a no-op — see the [Rate limiting](#rate-limiting) section below.\n696: \n697: | Scope | Limit |\n698: |---|---|\n699: | Memory writes | 60 req/min per API key |\n700: | Memory searches | 120 req/min per API key |\n701: | General reads | 300 req/min per API key |\n702: | Auth endpoints | 10 req/min per IP |\n703: | Global DDoS floor | 1000 req/min per IP |\n704: \n705: Exceeded limits return HTTP 429 with a `Retry-After` header.\n706: \n707: </details>\n708: \n709: ---\n710: \n711: <details>\n712: <summary>Configuration</summary>\n713: \n714: All configuration is via environment variables or `.env`. See `.env.example` for the full list.\n715: \n716: > **Migrating from a pre-1.0 deploy?** The legacy `ALLOYDB_*` env var names are still accepted as aliases — `POSTGRES_HOST` falls back to `ALLOYDB_HOST`, etc. Aliases will be dropped in a future major release.\n717: \n718: | Variable | Default | Description |\n719: |---|---|---|\n720: | `POSTGRES_HOST` | `127.0.0.1` | Database host |\n721: | `POSTGRES_PORT` | `5432` | Database port |\n722: | `POSTGRES_USER` | `memclaw` | Database user |\n723: | `POSTGRES_PASSWORD` | `changeme` | Database password |\n724: | `POSTGRES_DB` | `memclaw` | Database name |\n725: | `POSTGRES_USE_IAM_AUTH` | `false` | Use GCP IAM for DB auth (managed Postgres on GCP only) |\n726: | `ADMIN_API_KEY` | *(empty)* | Admin API key — bypasses tenant enforcement |\n727: | `EMBEDDING_PROVIDER` | `openai` | `openai`, `local`, or `fake` |\n728: | `ENTITY_EXTRACTION_PROVIDER` | `openai` | `openai`, `gemini`, `anthropic`, `openrouter`, `fake`, or `none` |\n729: | `ENTITY_EXTRACTION_MODEL` | `gpt-5.4-nano` | LLM model for enrichment and entity extraction |\n730: | `OPENAI_API_KEY` | — | Required for OpenAI embeddings and enrichment |\n731: | `USE_LLM_FOR_MEMORY_CREATION` | `true` | LLM auto-classifies type, weight, title, summary, tags on write |\n732: | `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | — | Required for Anthropic |\n733: | `OPENROUTER_API_KEY` | — | Required for OpenRouter |\n734: | `GEMINI_API_KEY` | — | Required for Gemini (Developer API, from AI Studio) |\n735: | `CORS_ORIGINS` | `http://localhost:3000` | Comma-separated allowed CORS origins |\n736: | `ENVIRONMENT` | `development` | `development` or `production` |\n737: | `SETTINGS_ENCRYPTION_KEY` | — | Fernet key for encrypting tenant settings. Required in production |\n738: | `PLATFORM_LLM_PROVIDER` | *(empty)* | Platform-default LLM: `openai`, `vertex`, or empty to disable |\n739: | `PLATFORM_LLM_MODEL` | *(empty)* | Model override (e.g. `gpt-5.4-nano`, `gemini-3.1-flash-lite-preview`) |\n740: | `PLATFORM_LLM_API_KEY` | — | OpenAI API key for the platform LLM singleton |\n741: | `PLATFORM_LLM_GCP_PROJECT_ID` | — | GCP project for platform Vertex LLM |\n742: | `PLATFORM_LLM_GCP_LOCATION` | `us-central1` | GCP region for platform Vertex LLM |\n743: | `PLATFORM_EMBEDDING_PROVIDER` | *(empty)* | Platform-default embeddings: `openai` or empty to disable |\n744: | `PLATFORM_EMBEDDING_MODEL` | *(empty)* | Embedding model override (e.g. `text-embedding-3-small`) |\n\n(Showing lines 690-744 of 965. Use offset=745 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\nThese headers are honored unconditionally — `core-api` must not be network-exposed without a gateway that strips them from untrusted callers.\n\n**Rate limiting (managed platform)**\n\nThese limits apply to the managed platform at `memclaw.net`. In the OSS edition, rate limiting is a no-op — see the [Rate limiting](#rate-limiting) section below.\n\n| Scope | Limit |\n|---|---|\n| Memory writes | 60 req/min per API key |\n| Memory searches | 120 req/min per API key |\n| General reads | 300 req/min per API key |\n| Auth endpoints | 10 req/min per IP |\n| Global DDoS floor | 1000 req/min per IP |\n\nExceeded limits return HTTP 429 with a `Retry-After` header.\n\n</details>\n\n---","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md","text":"\nThese headers are honored unconditionally — `core-api` must not be network-exposed without a gateway that strips them from untrusted callers.\n\n**Rate limiting (managed platform)**\n\nThese limits apply to the managed platform at `memclaw.net`. In the OSS edition, rate limiting is a no-op — see the [Rate limiting](#rate-limiting) section below.\n\n| Scope | Limit |\n|---|---|\n| Memory writes | 60 req/min per API key |\n| Memory searches | 120 req/min per API key |\n| General reads | 300 req/min per API key |\n| Auth endpoints | 10 req/min per IP |\n| Global DDoS floor | 1000 req/min per IP |\n\nExceeded limits return HTTP 429 with a `Retry-After` header.\n\n</details>\n\n---\n\n<details>\n<summary>Configuration</summary>\n\nAll configuration is via environment variables or `.env`. See `.env.example` for the full list.\n\n> **Migrating from a pre-1.0 deploy?** The legacy `ALLOYDB_*` env var names are still accepted as aliases — `POSTGRES_HOST` falls back to `ALLOYDB_HOST`, etc. Aliases will be dropped in a future major release.\n\n| Variable | Default | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| `POSTGRES_HOST` | `127.0.0.1` | Database host |\n| `POSTGRES_PORT` | `5432` | Database port |\n| `POSTGRES_USER` | `memclaw` | Database user |\n| `POSTGRES_PASSWORD` | `changeme` | Database password |\n| `POSTGRES_DB` | `memclaw` | Database name |\n| `POSTGRES_USE_IAM_AUTH` | `false` | Use GCP IAM for DB auth (managed Postgres on GCP only) |\n| `ADMIN_API_KEY` | *(empty)* | Admin API key — bypasses tenant enforcement |\n| `EMBEDDING_PROVIDER` | `openai` | `openai`, `local`, or `fake` |\n| `ENTITY_EXTRACTION_PROVIDER` | `openai` | `openai`, `gemini`, `anthropic`, `openrouter`, `fake`, or `none` |\n| `ENTITY_EXTRACTION_MODEL` | `gpt-5.4-nano` | LLM model for enrichment and entity extraction |\n| `OPENAI_API_KEY` | — | Required for OpenAI embeddings and enrichment |\n| `USE_LLM_FOR_MEMORY_CREATION` | `true` | LLM auto-classifies type, weight, title, summary, tags on write |\n| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | — | Required for Anthropic |\n| `OPENROUTER_API_KEY` | — | Required for OpenRouter |\n| `GEMINI_API_KEY` | — | Required for Gemini (Developer API, from AI Studio) |\n| `CORS_ORIGINS` | `http://localhost:3000` | Comma-separated allowed CORS origins |\n| `ENVIRONMENT` | `development` | `development` or `production` |\n| `SETTINGS_ENCRYPTION_KEY` | — | Fernet key for encrypting tenant settings. Required in production |\n| `PLATFORM_LLM_PROVIDER` | *(empty)* | Platform-default LLM: `openai`, `vertex`, or empty to disable |\n| `PLATFORM_LLM_MODEL` | *(empty)* | Model override (e.g. `gpt-5.4-nano`, `gemini-3.1-flash-lite-preview`) |\n| `PLATFORM_LLM_API_KEY` | — | OpenAI API key for the platform LLM singleton |\n| `PLATFORM_LLM_GCP_PROJECT_ID` | — | GCP project for platform Vertex LLM |\n| `PLATFORM_LLM_GCP_LOCATION` | `us-central1` | GCP region for platform Vertex LLM |\n| `PLATFORM_EMBEDDING_PROVIDER` | *(empty)* | Platform-default embeddings: `openai` or empty to disable |\n| `PLATFORM_EMBEDDING_MODEL` | *(empty)* | Embedding model override (e.g. `text-embedding-3-small`) |","lineStart":690,"lineEnd":744,"totalLines":965,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md","time":{"start":1780728479418,"end":1780728479424}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0864e1f84848cb91016a23c291e2808191b0f2fc78d2c8a66c"}},"id":"prt_e9bb03b290018E61CdIgkEwS6k","sessionID":"ses_164517a81ffemKHCVyXGgLqE5C","messageID":"msg_e9baf2985001z0btwIoqxLOoa9"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780728479676,"sessionID":"ses_164517a81ffemKHCVyXGgLqE5C","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_oDCJ0YjTCMeJXIdZ8FSHlGkK","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md","offset":798,"limit":45},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n798: | `memclaw_write` | ~2000ms | ~2000ms | ~2300ms |\n799: | `memclaw_recall` | ~650ms | ~640ms | ~670ms |\n800: | `memclaw_recall` (with `include_brief=true`) | ~1300ms | ~1200ms | ~2100ms |\n801: \n802: Write latency is dominated by LLM enrichment. Recall latency by the embedding API call.\n803: \n804: ```bash\n805: python scripts/latency_test.py --url http://localhost:8000 --api-key <admin-key> --runs 20\n806: ```\n807: \n808: </details>\n809: \n810: ---\n811: \n812: ## Public API & Stability\n813: \n814: MemClaw v1.x follows [SemVer 2.0.0](https://semver.org/spec/v2.0.0.html). The surfaces below are stable; everything else is internal and may change in any release.\n815: \n816: ### Stable surfaces\n817: \n818: #### MCP tools (12)\n819: \n820: The MCP server is mounted at `/mcp`. Tool names, parameter names, and the documented op-dispatch values are stable.\n821: \n822: | Tool | Purpose |\n823: |---|---|\n824: | `memclaw_recall` | Hybrid semantic + keyword search over memories, with optional LLM-summarised brief. |\n825: | `memclaw_write` | Single or batch (≤100) memory write; auto-enriched with type, title, summary, tags. |\n826: | `memclaw_manage` | Per-memory lifecycle, op-dispatched: `read` \\| `update` \\| `transition` \\| `delete` \\| `bulk_delete` \\| `lineage`. |\n827: | `memclaw_list` | Non-semantic enumeration with filters, sort, cursor pagination. |\n828: | `memclaw_doc` | Structured-document CRUD, op-dispatched: `write` \\| `read` \\| `query` \\| `delete` \\| `list_collections` \\| `search`. |\n829: | `memclaw_entity_get` | Look up a knowledge-graph entity by UUID. |\n830: | `memclaw_tune` | Read/update an agent's per-search profile (top_k, fts_weight, freshness, blend, …). |\n831: | `memclaw_insights` | Karpathy-Loop reflection: contradictions, failures, stale, divergence, patterns, discover. |\n832: | `memclaw_evolve` | Karpathy-Loop feedback: record an outcome (`success` \\| `failure` \\| `partial`) against memories. |\n833: | `memclaw_stats` | Aggregate counts: total + breakdowns by `type` / `agent` / `status`. Read-only. |\n834: | `memclaw_keystones` | Read mandatory governance rules for the current scope (tenant + fleet + agent merged). Call once per session. |\n835: | `memclaw_keystones_set` | Author/remove keystone rules, op-dispatched: `set` \\| `delete`. Trust ≥ 1 for self-authored `scope=agent`; ≥ 2 otherwise. |\n836: \n837: > Skill sharing uses the generic `memclaw_doc` surface — write/read/query/search/delete on `collection=\"skills\"`. The server validates the slug and embeds `data[\"summary\"]` for semantic discovery (with a back-compat fallback to `data[\"description\"]` for skills).\n838: \n839: #### REST endpoints\n840: \n841: All paths are prefixed with `/api/v1` unless noted. Request and response shapes documented in the OpenAPI schema at `/openapi.json` are part of the contract.\n842: \n\n(Showing lines 798-842 of 965. Use offset=843 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"| `memclaw_write` | ~2000ms | ~2000ms | ~2300ms |\n| `memclaw_recall` | ~650ms | ~640ms | ~670ms |\n| `memclaw_recall` (with `include_brief=true`) | ~1300ms | ~1200ms | ~2100ms |\n\nWrite latency is dominated by LLM enrichment. Recall latency by the embedding API call.\n\n```bash\npython scripts/latency_test.py --url http://localhost:8000 --api-key <admin-key> --runs 20\n```\n\n</details>\n\n---\n\n## Public API & Stability\n\nMemClaw v1.x follows [SemVer 2.0.0](https://semver.org/spec/v2.0.0.html). The surfaces below are stable; everything else is internal and may change in any release.\n\n### Stable surfaces\n","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md","text":"| `memclaw_write` | ~2000ms | ~2000ms | ~2300ms |\n| `memclaw_recall` | ~650ms | ~640ms | ~670ms |\n| `memclaw_recall` (with `include_brief=true`) | ~1300ms | ~1200ms | ~2100ms |\n\nWrite latency is dominated by LLM enrichment. Recall latency by the embedding API call.\n\n```bash\npython scripts/latency_test.py --url http://localhost:8000 --api-key <admin-key> --runs 20\n```\n\n</details>\n\n---\n\n## Public API & Stability\n\nMemClaw v1.x follows [SemVer 2.0.0](https://semver.org/spec/v2.0.0.html). The surfaces below are stable; everything else is internal and may change in any release.\n\n### Stable surfaces\n\n#### MCP tools (12)\n\nThe MCP server is mounted at `/mcp`. Tool names, parameter names, and the documented op-dispatch values are stable.\n\n| Tool | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `memclaw_recall` | Hybrid semantic + keyword search over memories, with optional LLM-summarised brief. |\n| `memclaw_write` | Single or batch (≤100) memory write; auto-enriched with type, title, summary, tags. |\n| `memclaw_manage` | Per-memory lifecycle, op-dispatched: `read` \\| `update` \\| `transition` \\| `delete` \\| `bulk_delete` \\| `lineage`. |\n| `memclaw_list` | Non-semantic enumeration with filters, sort, cursor pagination. |\n| `memclaw_doc` | Structured-document CRUD, op-dispatched: `write` \\| `read` \\| `query` \\| `delete` \\| `list_collections` \\| `search`. |\n| `memclaw_entity_get` | Look up a knowledge-graph entity by UUID. |\n| `memclaw_tune` | Read/update an agent's per-search profile (top_k, fts_weight, freshness, blend, …). |\n| `memclaw_insights` | Karpathy-Loop reflection: contradictions, failures, stale, divergence, patterns, discover. |\n| `memclaw_evolve` | Karpathy-Loop feedback: record an outcome (`success` \\| `failure` \\| `partial`) against memories. |\n| `memclaw_stats` | Aggregate counts: total + breakdowns by `type` / `agent` / `status`. Read-only. |\n| `memclaw_keystones` | Read mandatory governance rules for the current scope (tenant + fleet + agent merged). Call once per session. |\n| `memclaw_keystones_set` | Author/remove keystone rules, op-dispatched: `set` \\| `delete`. Trust ≥ 1 for self-authored `scope=agent`; ≥ 2 otherwise. |\n\n> Skill sharing uses the generic `memclaw_doc` surface — write/read/query/search/delete on `collection=\"skills\"`. The server validates the slug and embeds `data[\"summary\"]` for semantic discovery (with a back-compat fallback to `data[\"description\"]` for skills).\n\n#### REST endpoints\n\nAll paths are prefixed with `/api/v1` unless noted. Request and response shapes documented in the OpenAPI schema at `/openapi.json` are part of the contract.\n","lineStart":798,"lineEnd":842,"totalLines":965,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md","time":{"start":1780728479671,"end":1780728479675}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0864e1f84848cb91016a23c291e28c81918b4d4f9c987434f7"}},"id":"prt_e9bb03ecb001RSKlP0InnPwNLm","sessionID":"ses_164517a81ffemKHCVyXGgLqE5C","messageID":"msg_e9baf2985001z0btwIoqxLOoa9"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780728479735,"sessionID":"ses_164517a81ffemKHCVyXGgLqE5C","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_frZsuAE1JOia3WUxi2HT6cO1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md","offset":932,"limit":38},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n932: ## Rate limiting\n933: \n934: Rate limiting in the OSS edition is a **no-op** — all rate-limit decorators are identity\n935: functions that accept every request without throttling. For production deployments exposed to\n936: the internet, add rate limiting at your reverse proxy (nginx, Caddy, Cloudflare) or implement\n937: application-level limiting in `core-api/src/core_api/middleware/rate_limit.py`.\n938: \n939: ## Telemetry\n940: \n941: MemClaw **does not phone home** by default. No usage data, analytics, or tracking of any kind.\n942: \n943: If you set the `SENTRY_DSN` environment variable, [Sentry](https://sentry.io) error tracking\n944: is enabled — crash reports and performance traces are sent to your configured Sentry project.\n945: When `SENTRY_DSN` is empty (the default), Sentry is not initialized and no data leaves the\n946: server.\n947: \n948: ## Contributing\n949: \n950: We welcome contributions! See [CONTRIBUTING.md](CONTRIBUTING.md) for guidelines, development setup, and how to submit PRs.\n951: \n952: ---\n953: \n954: ## License\n955: \n956: MemClaw is licensed under the [Apache License, Version 2.0](LICENSE).\n957: \n958: See [NOTICE](NOTICE) for copyright and third-party attributions.\n959: \n960: ## Trademarks\n961: \n962: \"MemClaw\" and \"Caura\" are trademarks of Caura. The Apache License 2.0 grants\n963: permission to use the source code but does not grant permission to use these\n964: names, logos, or branding in a way that suggests endorsement of, or affiliation\n965: with, any derivative work. See Apache License 2.0 §6 for the full legal terms.\n\n(End of file - total 965 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"## Rate limiting\n\nRate limiting in the OSS edition is a **no-op** — all rate-limit decorators are identity\nfunctions that accept every request without throttling. For production deployments exposed to\nthe internet, add rate limiting at your reverse proxy (nginx, Caddy, Cloudflare) or implement\napplication-level limiting in `core-api/src/core_api/middleware/rate_limit.py`.\n\n## Telemetry\n\nMemClaw **does not phone home** by default. No usage data, analytics, or tracking of any kind.\n\nIf you set the `SENTRY_DSN` environment variable, [Sentry](https://sentry.io) error tracking\nis enabled — crash reports and performance traces are sent to your configured Sentry project.\nWhen `SENTRY_DSN` is empty (the default), Sentry is not initialized and no data leaves the\nserver.\n\n## Contributing\n\nWe welcome contributions! See [CONTRIBUTING.md](CONTRIBUTING.md) for guidelines, development setup, and how to submit PRs.\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md","text":"## Rate limiting\n\nRate limiting in the OSS edition is a **no-op** — all rate-limit decorators are identity\nfunctions that accept every request without throttling. For production deployments exposed to\nthe internet, add rate limiting at your reverse proxy (nginx, Caddy, Cloudflare) or implement\napplication-level limiting in `core-api/src/core_api/middleware/rate_limit.py`.\n\n## Telemetry\n\nMemClaw **does not phone home** by default. No usage data, analytics, or tracking of any kind.\n\nIf you set the `SENTRY_DSN` environment variable, [Sentry](https://sentry.io) error tracking\nis enabled — crash reports and performance traces are sent to your configured Sentry project.\nWhen `SENTRY_DSN` is empty (the default), Sentry is not initialized and no data leaves the\nserver.\n\n## Contributing\n\nWe welcome contributions! See [CONTRIBUTING.md](CONTRIBUTING.md) for guidelines, development setup, and how to submit PRs.\n\n---\n\n## License\n\nMemClaw is licensed under the [Apache License, Version 2.0](LICENSE).\n\nSee [NOTICE](NOTICE) for copyright and third-party attributions.\n\n## Trademarks\n\n\"MemClaw\" and \"Caura\" are trademarks of Caura. The Apache License 2.0 grants\npermission to use the source code but does not grant permission to use these\nnames, logos, or branding in a way that suggests endorsement of, or affiliation\nwith, any derivative work. See Apache License 2.0 §6 for the full legal terms.","lineStart":932,"lineEnd":965,"totalLines":965,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md","time":{"start":1780728479730,"end":1780728479734}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0864e1f84848cb91016a23c291e2948191a5373cb7af2aa464"}},"id":"prt_e9bb03fc80013VScmVJ17OH6qm","sessionID":"ses_164517a81ffemKHCVyXGgLqE5C","messageID":"msg_e9baf2985001z0btwIoqxLOoa9"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780728479802,"sessionID":"ses_164517a81ffemKHCVyXGgLqE5C","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_vRNHIdXPVOGjHJSwXhPpiPwp","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/routes/memories.py","offset":1380,"limit":370},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/routes/memories.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1380:         if \"metadata\" not in body.model_fields_set:\n1381:             raise HTTPException(\n1382:                 status_code=422,\n1383:                 detail=\"metadata_mode is only valid when metadata is also provided\",\n1384:             )\n1385:         body.metadata_mode = metadata_mode\n1386:     if auth.tenant_id:  # skip usage metering for admin\n1387:         await check_and_increment(db, tenant_id, \"write\")\n1388:     # Authenticated agent identity (gateway X-Agent-ID) takes precedence over\n1389:     # the caller-supplied query param for trust/fleet enforcement.\n1390:     return await update_memory(\n1391:         db,\n1392:         memory_id,\n1393:         tenant_id,\n1394:         body,\n1395:         agent_id=(auth.agent_id or agent_id) if auth.tenant_id else None,\n1396:     )\n1397: \n1398: \n1399: @router.post(\"/search\", response_model=SearchResponse)\n1400: @search_limit\n1401: async def search(\n1402:     request: Request,\n1403:     body: SearchRequest,\n1404:     response: Response,\n1405:     auth: AuthContext = Depends(get_auth_context),\n1406:     db: AsyncSession = Depends(get_db),\n1407: ):\n1408:     # Read endpoint — honors cross-tenant readable set. The SQL\n1409:     # widens to readable_tenant_ids inside search_memories so the\n1410:     # body.tenant_id can be any tenant the caller may read from\n1411:     # (typically home, but explicit source queries work too).\n1412:     auth.enforce_readable_tenant(body.tenant_id)\n1413:     async with per_tenant_slot(\"search\", body.tenant_id):\n1414:         return await _search_inner(body, response, auth, db)\n1415: \n1416: \n1417: async def _search_inner(\n1418:     body: SearchRequest,\n1419:     response: Response,\n1420:     auth: AuthContext,\n1421:     db: AsyncSession,\n1422: ):\n1423:     usage = None\n1424:     _agent = None\n1425:     # Effective caller identity for scope/fleet enforcement: an explicit\n1426:     # filter_agent_id, else the gateway-authenticated agent (auth.agent_id).\n1427:     # Falling back to auth.agent_id closes the search side of the BOLA chain —\n1428:     # a constrained agent that OMITS filter_agent_id must still be fleet- and\n1429:     # scope_agent-bound, not handed tenant-wide content (search returns full\n1430:     # content, so this is a direct disclosure, not just id harvesting). A\n1431:     # tenant/user credential (auth.agent_id None, no filter) keeps full-tenant\n1432:     # search, unchanged.\n1433:     eff_agent_id = body.filter_agent_id or auth.agent_id\n1434:     if auth.tenant_id:  # skip for admin\n1435:         if eff_agent_id:\n1436:             fleet_id_hint = body.fleet_ids[0] if body.fleet_ids and len(body.fleet_ids) == 1 else None\n1437:             _agent = await get_or_create_agent(db, body.tenant_id, eff_agent_id, fleet_id_hint)\n1438:             if not body.fleet_ids and _agent.get(\"fleet_id\") and _agent.get(\"trust_level\", 0) < 2:\n1439:                 body.fleet_ids = [_agent[\"fleet_id\"]]  # Force fleet scoping for trust < 2\n1440:             if body.fleet_ids and len(body.fleet_ids) == 1:\n1441:                 await enforce_fleet_read(db, body.tenant_id, eff_agent_id, body.fleet_ids[0])\n1442:         usage = await check_and_increment(db, body.tenant_id, \"search\")\n1443:     if usage:\n1444:         response.headers[\"X-RateLimit-Limit\"] = str(usage.get(\"limit\", \"unlimited\"))\n1445:         response.headers[\"X-RateLimit-Remaining\"] = str(usage.get(\"remaining\", \"unlimited\"))\n1446:     from core_api.services.organization_settings import resolve_config\n1447: \n1448:     t_start = time.perf_counter()\n1449:     success = True\n1450:     results: list = []\n1451:     try:\n1452:         config = await resolve_config(db, body.tenant_id)\n1453:         # Widen the read predicate when the caller authenticated with\n1454:         # a cross-tenant key. Single-tenant keys leave\n1455:         # ``readable_tenant_ids = [tenant_id]`` so this is a no-op.\n1456:         results = await search_memories(\n1457:             db,\n1458:             tenant_id=body.tenant_id,\n1459:             query=body.query,\n1460:             fleet_ids=body.fleet_ids,\n1461:             filter_agent_id=body.filter_agent_id,\n1462:             # Visibility identity is the authenticated agent (not just an\n1463:             # explicit filter) so the caller sees its own scope_agent rows and\n1464:             # nobody else's, even when filter_agent_id is omitted.\n1465:             caller_agent_id=eff_agent_id,\n1466:             memory_type_filter=body.memory_type_filter,\n1467:             status_filter=body.status_filter,\n1468:             valid_at=body.valid_at,\n1469:             top_k=body.top_k,\n1470:             recall_boost=config.recall_boost,\n1471:             graph_expand=config.graph_expand,\n1472:             tenant_config=config,\n1473:             search_profile=_agent.get(\"search_profile\") if _agent else None,\n1474:             readable_tenant_ids=auth.readable_tenant_ids if auth.is_cross_tenant_read else None,\n1475:         )\n1476:     except HTTPException:\n1477:         # Auth / tenant errors raised downstream are expected outcomes,\n1478:         # not DB/network failures — don't flag them as ``error=True``.\n1479:         raise\n1480:     except Exception:\n1481:         success = False\n1482:         raise\n1483:     finally:\n1484:         if logger.isEnabledFor(logging.INFO):\n1485:             logger.info(\n1486:                 \"search request completed\",\n1487:                 extra={\n1488:                     \"path\": \"memory-search\",\n1489:                     \"tenant_id\": body.tenant_id,\n1490:                     \"top_k\": body.top_k,\n1491:                     \"row_count\": len(results),\n1492:                     \"total_ms\": (time.perf_counter() - t_start) * 1000,\n1493:                     \"error\": not success,\n1494:                 },\n1495:             )\n1496:     return SearchResponse(items=results)\n1497: \n1498: \n1499: @router.post(\"/ingest/preview\")\n1500: async def ingest_preview_endpoint(\n1501:     body: IngestRequest,\n1502:     auth: AuthContext = Depends(get_auth_context),\n1503:     db: AsyncSession = Depends(get_db),\n1504: ):\n1505:     \"\"\"Extract facts from a URL or text for preview (no writes).\n1506: \n1507:     Body size cap: enforced upstream by ``IngestBodySizeMiddleware`` (PR #9).\n1508:     \"\"\"\n1509:     auth.enforce_read_only()\n1510:     auth.enforce_usage_limits()\n1511:     auth.enforce_tenant(body.tenant_id)\n1512:     return await ingest_preview(db, body)\n1513: \n1514: \n1515: @router.post(\"/ingest/commit\")\n1516: @write_limit\n1517: async def ingest_commit_endpoint(\n1518:     request: Request,\n1519:     body: IngestCommitRequest,\n1520:     auth: AuthContext = Depends(get_auth_context),\n1521:     db: AsyncSession = Depends(get_db),\n1522: ):\n1523:     \"\"\"Write previewed facts as memories.\"\"\"\n1524:     auth.enforce_read_only()\n1525:     auth.enforce_usage_limits()\n1526:     auth.enforce_tenant(body.tenant_id)\n1527:     if auth.tenant_id:  # skip for admin\n1528:         await check_and_increment(db, body.tenant_id, \"write\")\n1529:     return await ingest_commit(db, body)\n1530: \n1531: \n1532: @router.post(\"/ingest/file\")\n1533: async def ingest_file_endpoint(\n1534:     file: UploadFile = File(...),\n1535:     tenant_id: str = Form(...),\n1536:     focus: str | None = Form(None),\n1537:     fleet_id: str | None = Form(None),\n1538:     agent_id: str | None = Form(None),\n1539:     auth: AuthContext = Depends(get_auth_context),\n1540:     db: AsyncSession = Depends(get_db),\n1541: ):\n1542:     \"\"\"PR #9: multipart file upload entry point.\n1543: \n1544:     Accepts the same 3 MB cap as JSON / URL ingest. Supported MIMEs:\n1545:     - Text formats (md, txt, csv, html): decoded directly.\n1546:     - Binary formats (pdf, docx, pptx, xlsx, epub, rtf, odt): routed\n1547:       through Kreuzberg for text extraction.\n1548: \n1549:     The uploaded file's ``Content-Type`` drives dispatch. The Content-Length\n1550:     cap is enforced upstream by ``IngestBodySizeMiddleware``; we re-check\n1551:     the extracted payload size here for defense in depth (multipart envelope\n1552:     overhead can hide the real payload size from the request header).\n1553:     \"\"\"\n1554:     auth.enforce_read_only()\n1555:     auth.enforce_usage_limits()\n1556:     auth.enforce_tenant(tenant_id)\n1557: \n1558:     body = await file.read()\n1559:     if len(body) > INGEST_MAX_INPUT_BYTES:\n1560:         max_mb = INGEST_MAX_INPUT_BYTES // 1_000_000\n1561:         raise HTTPException(\n1562:             status_code=413,\n1563:             detail=f\"File must be {max_mb} MB or under (got {len(body):,} bytes).\",\n1564:         )\n1565: \n1566:     mime = (file.content_type or \"\").split(\";\")[0].strip().lower()\n1567:     if mime in BINARY_INGEST_MIME_TYPES:\n1568:         text = await _extract_with_kreuzberg(body, mime)\n1569:     elif mime in TEXT_INGEST_MIME_TYPES:\n1570:         text = decode_text_body(body, mime)\n1571:     else:\n1572:         raise HTTPException(\n1573:             status_code=422,\n1574:             detail=(f\"Unsupported content type: {mime}. Allowed: {sorted(ALLOWED_INGEST_MIME_TYPES)}\"),\n1575:         )\n1576: \n1577:     # IngestRequest.agent_id has a non-None default (\"ingest-agent\"); pass\n1578:     # only when the form actually carried one to avoid clobbering the default.\n1579:     kwargs: dict = {\"tenant_id\": tenant_id, \"content\": text, \"focus\": focus, \"fleet_id\": fleet_id}\n1580:     if agent_id is not None:\n1581:         kwargs[\"agent_id\"] = agent_id\n1582:     # Preserve the original filename as ``upload:<filename>`` so each\n1583:     # resulting memory's ``source_uri`` says where it came from instead\n1584:     # of the generic ``\"text-input\"`` marker. ``file.filename`` can be\n1585:     # absent / empty when the client doesn't send a multipart name, in\n1586:     # which case we fall back to a generic ``\"upload\"`` label.\n1587:     filename = (file.filename or \"\").strip() or None\n1588:     kwargs[\"source_uri\"] = f\"upload:{filename}\" if filename else \"upload\"\n1589:     req = IngestRequest(**kwargs)\n1590:     return await ingest_preview(db, req)\n1591: \n1592: \n1593: @router.post(\"/ingest/undo/{run_id}\")\n1594: async def ingest_undo_endpoint(\n1595:     run_id: str,\n1596:     tenant_id: str = Query(...),\n1597:     auth: AuthContext = Depends(get_auth_context),\n1598:     db: AsyncSession = Depends(get_db),\n1599: ):\n1600:     \"\"\"A3 (PR #6): soft-delete every memory tagged with the given run_id.\n1601: \n1602:     The undo lever for an entire ingest batch. Filters by the top-level\n1603:     ``Memory.run_id`` column (indexed as of the parent-doc PR) AND\n1604:     ``metadata.source = \"ingest\"`` (belt-and-braces — prevents non-ingest\n1605:     memories sharing a run_id from being touched) AND tenant_id ownership.\n1606: \n1607:     Also deletes the parent ``documents`` row for the batch\n1608:     (``collection='ingest-sources'``, ``doc_id=<run_id>``) on a best-effort\n1609:     basis — a missing parent isn't an error since older batches predate\n1610:     the parent-doc PR.\n1611: \n1612:     Returns ``{\"deleted\": N, \"run_id\": \"...\"}``. ``deleted=0`` is a valid\n1613:     response (no rows matched — already cleaned up or never existed).\n1614:     \"\"\"\n1615:     auth.enforce_read_only()\n1616:     auth.enforce_tenant(tenant_id)\n1617: \n1618:     stmt = (\n1619:         update(Memory)\n1620:         .where(\n1621:             Memory.tenant_id == tenant_id,\n1622:             Memory.deleted_at.is_(None),\n1623:             Memory.run_id == run_id,\n1624:             Memory.metadata_[\"source\"].astext == \"ingest\",\n1625:         )\n1626:         .values(deleted_at=datetime.now(UTC), status=\"deleted\")\n1627:     )\n1628:     result = await db.execute(stmt)\n1629:     deleted_count = result.rowcount\n1630: \n1631:     # Delete the parent Document for this batch (introduced by the\n1632:     # parent-doc PR). Best-effort: older batches predate the parent-doc\n1633:     # write and won't have one, which is fine — undo on those still\n1634:     # soft-deletes the memories, just without a parent record to drop.\n1635:     try:\n1636:         sc = get_storage_client()\n1637:         await sc.delete_document(tenant_id=tenant_id, collection=INGEST_DOCUMENTS_COLLECTION, doc_id=run_id)\n1638:     except Exception:\n1639:         logger.info(\n1640:             \"ingest_undo: parent Document delete failed or no-op (run_id=%s) — \"\n1641:             \"memories soft-deleted regardless\",\n1642:             run_id,\n1643:             exc_info=False,\n1644:         )\n1645: \n1646:     await log_action(\n1647:         db,\n1648:         tenant_id=tenant_id,\n1649:         action=\"ingest_undo\",\n1650:         resource_type=\"memory\",\n1651:         detail={\"run_id\": run_id, \"count\": deleted_count},\n1652:     )\n1653:     await db.commit()\n1654:     return {\"deleted\": deleted_count, \"run_id\": run_id}\n1655: \n1656: \n1657: @router.post(\"/recall\")\n1658: @search_limit\n1659: async def recall_endpoint(\n1660:     request: Request,\n1661:     body: SearchRequest,\n1662:     auth: AuthContext = Depends(get_auth_context),\n1663:     db: AsyncSession = Depends(get_db),\n1664: ):\n1665:     \"\"\"Search memories and return an LLM-synthesized context summary.\n1666: \n1667:     Audit P3 (extended to REST): the legacy ``recall(db, ...)`` wrapper\n1668:     held the FastAPI-injected DB session across the multi-second LLM\n1669:     brief, pinning a pooled connection. Load-test gate flagged\n1670:     ``slo-p95-recall_brief`` (6.9 s vs 5 s target) and\n1671:     ``noisy-neighbor-write`` (6.49x regression under search storm) —\n1672:     both rooted in the same pool-pinning pattern.\n1673: \n1674:     Mitigation: do the DB-bound search inside the request session,\n1675:     explicitly ``await db.close()`` to return the connection to the\n1676:     pool, then call ``summarize_memories`` (the no-DB LLM helper from\n1677:     PR #228). ``AsyncSession.close()`` is idempotent, so FastAPI's\n1678:     dependency cleanup at request end runs harmlessly.\n1679:     \"\"\"\n1680:     # Read endpoint — readable set widening applies (see /search).\n1681:     auth.enforce_readable_tenant(body.tenant_id)\n1682:     if auth.tenant_id:\n1683:         if body.filter_agent_id:\n1684:             fleet_id_hint = body.fleet_ids[0] if body.fleet_ids and len(body.fleet_ids) == 1 else None\n1685:             _agent = await get_or_create_agent(db, body.tenant_id, body.filter_agent_id, fleet_id_hint)\n1686:             if not body.fleet_ids and _agent.get(\"fleet_id\") and _agent.get(\"trust_level\", 0) < 2:\n1687:                 body.fleet_ids = [_agent[\"fleet_id\"]]\n1688:             if body.fleet_ids and len(body.fleet_ids) == 1:\n1689:                 await enforce_fleet_read(db, body.tenant_id, body.filter_agent_id, body.fleet_ids[0])\n1690:         await check_and_increment(db, body.tenant_id, \"search\")\n1691: \n1692:     from core_api.services.memory_service import search_memories\n1693:     from core_api.services.organization_settings import resolve_config\n1694:     from core_api.services.recall_service import summarize_memories\n1695: \n1696:     t0 = time.perf_counter()\n1697: \n1698:     # ── Phase 1: DB-bound — config + search ──────────────────────\n1699:     config = await resolve_config(db, body.tenant_id)\n1700:     memories = await search_memories(\n1701:         db,\n1702:         tenant_id=body.tenant_id,\n1703:         query=body.query,\n1704:         fleet_ids=body.fleet_ids,\n1705:         filter_agent_id=body.filter_agent_id,\n1706:         caller_agent_id=body.filter_agent_id,\n1707:         memory_type_filter=body.memory_type_filter,\n1708:         status_filter=body.status_filter,\n1709:         top_k=body.top_k,\n1710:         valid_at=body.valid_at,\n1711:         recall_boost=config.recall_boost,\n1712:         graph_expand=config.graph_expand,\n1713:         tenant_config=config,\n1714:         readable_tenant_ids=auth.readable_tenant_ids if auth.is_cross_tenant_read else None,\n1715:     )\n1716: \n1717:     # Release the pooled DB connection before the LLM round-trip.\n1718:     # FastAPI's outer ``get_db`` ``async with`` will re-close on exit —\n1719:     # idempotent, so it's a no-op there.\n1720:     await db.close()\n1721: \n1722:     # ── Phase 2: LLM brief (no DB held) ──────────────────────────\n1723:     return await summarize_memories(\n1724:         memories,\n1725:         body.query,\n1726:         config,\n1727:         valid_at=body.valid_at,\n1728:         top_k=body.top_k,\n1729:         t0=t0,\n1730:     )\n1731: \n1732: \n1733: # ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n1734: # Redistribute\n1735: # ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n1736: \n1737: \n1738: @router.post(\"/memories/redistribute\", response_model=RedistributeResponse)\n1739: async def redistribute_memories(\n1740:     body: RedistributeRequest,\n1741:     tenant_id: str = Query(...),\n1742:     agent_id: str = Query(..., description=\"Requesting agent (must be trust_level >= 3)\"),\n1743:     auth: AuthContext = Depends(get_auth_context),\n1744:     db: AsyncSession = Depends(get_db),\n1745: ):\n1746:     \"\"\"Bulk-reassign memories to a different agent.\n1747: \n1748:     Admin-only (trust_level >= 3).  Moves memories to ``target_agent_id``,\n1749:     auto-promoting ``scope_agent`` → ``scope_team`` to prevent data loss.\n\n(Showing lines 1380-1749 of 2023. Use offset=1750 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"        if \"metadata\" not in body.model_fields_set:\n            raise HTTPException(\n                status_code=422,\n                detail=\"metadata_mode is only valid when metadata is also provided\",\n            )\n        body.metadata_mode = metadata_mode\n    if auth.tenant_id:  # skip usage metering for admin\n        await check_and_increment(db, tenant_id, \"write\")\n    # Authenticated agent identity (gateway X-Agent-ID) takes precedence over\n    # the caller-supplied query param for trust/fleet enforcement.\n    return await update_memory(\n        db,\n        memory_id,\n        tenant_id,\n        body,\n        agent_id=(auth.agent_id or agent_id) if auth.tenant_id else None,\n    )\n\n\n@router.post(\"/search\", response_model=SearchResponse)","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/routes/memories.py","text":"        if \"metadata\" not in body.model_fields_set:\n            raise HTTPException(\n                status_code=422,\n                detail=\"metadata_mode is only valid when metadata is also provided\",\n            )\n        body.metadata_mode = metadata_mode\n    if auth.tenant_id:  # skip usage metering for admin\n        await check_and_increment(db, tenant_id, \"write\")\n    # Authenticated agent identity (gateway X-Agent-ID) takes precedence over\n    # the caller-supplied query param for trust/fleet enforcement.\n    return await update_memory(\n        db,\n        memory_id,\n        tenant_id,\n        body,\n        agent_id=(auth.agent_id or agent_id) if auth.tenant_id else None,\n    )\n\n\n@router.post(\"/search\", response_model=SearchResponse)\n@search_limit\nasync def search(\n    request: Request,\n    body: SearchRequest,\n    response: Response,\n    auth: AuthContext = Depends(get_auth_context),\n    db: AsyncSession = Depends(get_db),\n):\n    # Read endpoint — honors cross-tenant readable set. The SQL\n    # widens to readable_tenant_ids inside search_memories so the\n    # body.tenant_id can be any tenant the caller may read from\n    # (typically home, but explicit source queries work too).\n    auth.enforce_readable_tenant(body.tenant_id)\n    async with per_tenant_slot(\"search\", body.tenant_id):\n        return await _search_inner(body, response, auth, db)\n\n\nasync def _search_inner(\n    body: SearchRequest,\n    response: Response,\n    auth: AuthContext,\n    db: AsyncSession,\n):\n    usage = None\n    _agent = None\n    # Effective caller identity for scope/fleet enforcement: an explicit\n    # filter_agent_id, else the gateway-authenticated agent (auth.agent_id).\n    # Falling back to auth.agent_id closes the search side of the BOLA chain —\n    # a constrained agent that OMITS filter_agent_id must still be fleet- and\n    # scope_agent-bound, not handed tenant-wide content (search returns full\n    # content, so this is a direct disclosure, not just id harvesting). A\n    # tenant/user credential (auth.agent_id None, no filter) keeps full-tenant\n    # search, unchanged.\n    eff_agent_id = body.filter_agent_id or auth.agent_id\n    if auth.tenant_id:  # skip for admin\n        if eff_agent_id:\n            fleet_id_hint = body.fleet_ids[0] if body.fleet_ids and len(body.fleet_ids) == 1 else None\n            _agent = await get_or_create_agent(db, body.tenant_id, eff_agent_id, fleet_id_hint)\n            if not body.fleet_ids and _agent.get(\"fleet_id\") and _agent.get(\"trust_level\", 0) < 2:\n                body.fleet_ids = [_agent[\"fleet_id\"]]  # Force fleet scoping for trust < 2\n            if body.fleet_ids and len(body.fleet_ids) == 1:\n                await enforce_fleet_read(db, body.tenant_id, eff_agent_id, body.fleet_ids[0])\n        usage = await check_and_increment(db, body.tenant_id, \"search\")\n    if usage:\n        response.headers[\"X-RateLimit-Limit\"] = str(usage.get(\"limit\", \"unlimited\"))\n        response.headers[\"X-RateLimit-Remaining\"] = str(usage.get(\"remaining\", \"unlimited\"))\n    from core_api.services.organization_settings import resolve_config\n\n    t_start = time.perf_counter()\n    success = True\n    results: list = []\n    try:\n        config = await resolve_config(db, body.tenant_id)\n        # Widen the read predicate when the caller authenticated with\n        # a cross-tenant key. Single-tenant keys leave\n        # ``readable_tenant_ids = [tenant_id]`` so this is a no-op.\n        results = await search_memories(\n            db,\n            tenant_id=body.tenant_id,\n            query=body.query,\n            fleet_ids=body.fleet_ids,\n            filter_agent_id=body.filter_agent_id,\n            # Visibility identity is the authenticated agent (not just an\n            # explicit filter) so the caller sees its own scope_agent rows and\n            # nobody else's, even when filter_agent_id is omitted.\n            caller_agent_id=eff_agent_id,\n            memory_type_filter=body.memory_type_filter,\n            status_filter=body.status_filter,\n            valid_at=body.valid_at,\n            top_k=body.top_k,\n            recall_boost=config.recall_boost,\n            graph_expand=config.graph_expand,\n            tenant_config=config,\n            search_profile=_agent.get(\"search_profile\") if _agent else None,\n            readable_tenant_ids=auth.readable_tenant_ids if auth.is_cross_tenant_read else None,\n        )\n    except HTTPException:\n        # Auth / tenant errors raised downstream are expected outcomes,\n        # not DB/network failures — don't flag them as ``error=True``.\n        raise\n    except Exception:\n        success = False\n        raise\n    finally:\n        if logger.isEnabledFor(logging.INFO):\n            logger.info(\n                \"search request completed\",\n                extra={\n                    \"path\": \"memory-search\",\n                    \"tenant_id\": body.tenant_id,\n                    \"top_k\": body.top_k,\n                    \"row_count\": len(results),\n                    \"total_ms\": (time.perf_counter() - t_start) * 1000,\n                    \"error\": not success,\n                },\n            )\n    return SearchResponse(items=results)\n\n\n@router.post(\"/ingest/preview\")\nasync def ingest_preview_endpoint(\n    body: IngestRequest,\n    auth: AuthContext = Depends(get_auth_context),\n    db: AsyncSession = Depends(get_db),\n):\n    \"\"\"Extract facts from a URL or text for preview (no writes).\n\n    Body size cap: enforced upstream by ``IngestBodySizeMiddleware`` (PR #9).\n    \"\"\"\n    auth.enforce_read_only()\n    auth.enforce_usage_limits()\n    auth.enforce_tenant(body.tenant_id)\n    return await ingest_preview(db, body)\n\n\n@router.post(\"/ingest/commit\")\n@write_limit\nasync def ingest_commit_endpoint(\n    request: Request,\n    body: IngestCommitRequest,\n    auth: AuthContext = Depends(get_auth_context),\n    db: AsyncSession = Depends(get_db),\n):\n    \"\"\"Write previewed facts as memories.\"\"\"\n    auth.enforce_read_only()\n    auth.enforce_usage_limits()\n    auth.enforce_tenant(body.tenant_id)\n    if auth.tenant_id:  # skip for admin\n        await check_and_increment(db, body.tenant_id, \"write\")\n    return await ingest_commit(db, body)\n\n\n@router.post(\"/ingest/file\")\nasync def ingest_file_endpoint(\n    file: UploadFile = File(...),\n    tenant_id: str = Form(...),\n    focus: str | None = Form(None),\n    fleet_id: str | None = Form(None),\n    agent_id: str | None = Form(None),\n    auth: AuthContext = Depends(get_auth_context),\n    db: AsyncSession = Depends(get_db),\n):\n    \"\"\"PR #9: multipart file upload entry point.\n\n    Accepts the same 3 MB cap as JSON / URL ingest. Supported MIMEs:\n    - Text formats (md, txt, csv, html): decoded directly.\n    - Binary formats (pdf, docx, pptx, xlsx, epub, rtf, odt): routed\n      through Kreuzberg for text extraction.\n\n    The uploaded file's ``Content-Type`` drives dispatch. The Content-Length\n    cap is enforced upstream by ``IngestBodySizeMiddleware``; we re-check\n    the extracted payload size here for defense in depth (multipart envelope\n    overhead can hide the real payload size from the request header).\n    \"\"\"\n    auth.enforce_read_only()\n    auth.enforce_usage_limits()\n    auth.enforce_tenant(tenant_id)\n\n    body = await file.read()\n    if len(body) > INGEST_MAX_INPUT_BYTES:\n        max_mb = INGEST_MAX_INPUT_BYTES // 1_000_000\n        raise HTTPException(\n            status_code=413,\n            detail=f\"File must be {max_mb} MB or under (got {len(body):,} bytes).\",\n        )\n\n    mime = (file.content_type or \"\").split(\";\")[0].strip().lower()\n    if mime in BINARY_INGEST_MIME_TYPES:\n        text = await _extract_with_kreuzberg(body, mime)\n    elif mime in TEXT_INGEST_MIME_TYPES:\n        text = decode_text_body(body, mime)\n    else:\n        raise HTTPException(\n            status_code=422,\n            detail=(f\"Unsupported content type: {mime}. Allowed: {sorted(ALLOWED_INGEST_MIME_TYPES)}\"),\n        )\n\n    # IngestRequest.agent_id has a non-None default (\"ingest-agent\"); pass\n    # only when the form actually carried one to avoid clobbering the default.\n    kwargs: dict = {\"tenant_id\": tenant_id, \"content\": text, \"focus\": focus, \"fleet_id\": fleet_id}\n    if agent_id is not None:\n        kwargs[\"agent_id\"] = agent_id\n    # Preserve the original filename as ``upload:<filename>`` so each\n    # resulting memory's ``source_uri`` says where it came from instead\n    # of the generic ``\"text-input\"`` marker. ``file.filename`` can be\n    # absent / empty when the client doesn't send a multipart name, in\n    # which case we fall back to a generic ``\"upload\"`` label.\n    filename = (file.filename or \"\").strip() or None\n    kwargs[\"source_uri\"] = f\"upload:{filename}\" if filename else \"upload\"\n    req = IngestRequest(**kwargs)\n    return await ingest_preview(db, req)\n\n\n@router.post(\"/ingest/undo/{run_id}\")\nasync def ingest_undo_endpoint(\n    run_id: str,\n    tenant_id: str = Query(...),\n    auth: AuthContext = Depends(get_auth_context),\n    db: AsyncSession = Depends(get_db),\n):\n    \"\"\"A3 (PR #6): soft-delete every memory tagged with the given run_id.\n\n    The undo lever for an entire ingest batch. Filters by the top-level\n    ``Memory.run_id`` column (indexed as of the parent-doc PR) AND\n    ``metadata.source = \"ingest\"`` (belt-and-braces — prevents non-ingest\n    memories sharing a run_id from being touched) AND tenant_id ownership.\n\n    Also deletes the parent ``documents`` row for the batch\n    (``collection='ingest-sources'``, ``doc_id=<run_id>``) on a best-effort\n    basis — a missing parent isn't an error since older batches predate\n    the parent-doc PR.\n\n    Returns ``{\"deleted\": N, \"run_id\": \"...\"}``. ``deleted=0`` is a valid\n    response (no rows matched — already cleaned up or never existed).\n    \"\"\"\n    auth.enforce_read_only()\n    auth.enforce_tenant(tenant_id)\n\n    stmt = (\n        update(Memory)\n        .where(\n            Memory.tenant_id == tenant_id,\n            Memory.deleted_at.is_(None),\n            Memory.run_id == run_id,\n            Memory.metadata_[\"source\"].astext == \"ingest\",\n        )\n        .values(deleted_at=datetime.now(UTC), status=\"deleted\")\n    )\n    result = await db.execute(stmt)\n    deleted_count = result.rowcount\n\n    # Delete the parent Document for this batch (introduced by the\n    # parent-doc PR). Best-effort: older batches predate the parent-doc\n    # write and won't have one, which is fine — undo on those still\n    # soft-deletes the memories, just without a parent record to drop.\n    try:\n        sc = get_storage_client()\n        await sc.delete_document(tenant_id=tenant_id, collection=INGEST_DOCUMENTS_COLLECTION, doc_id=run_id)\n    except Exception:\n        logger.info(\n            \"ingest_undo: parent Document delete failed or no-op (run_id=%s) — \"\n            \"memories soft-deleted regardless\",\n            run_id,\n            exc_info=False,\n        )\n\n    await log_action(\n        db,\n        tenant_id=tenant_id,\n        action=\"ingest_undo\",\n        resource_type=\"memory\",\n        detail={\"run_id\": run_id, \"count\": deleted_count},\n    )\n    await db.commit()\n    return {\"deleted\": deleted_count, \"run_id\": run_id}\n\n\n@router.post(\"/recall\")\n@search_limit\nasync def recall_endpoint(\n    request: Request,\n    body: SearchRequest,\n    auth: AuthContext = Depends(get_auth_context),\n    db: AsyncSession = Depends(get_db),\n):\n    \"\"\"Search memories and return an LLM-synthesized context summary.\n\n    Audit P3 (extended to REST): the legacy ``recall(db, ...)`` wrapper\n    held the FastAPI-injected DB session across the multi-second LLM\n    brief, pinning a pooled connection. Load-test gate flagged\n    ``slo-p95-recall_brief`` (6.9 s vs 5 s target) and\n    ``noisy-neighbor-write`` (6.49x regression under search storm) —\n    both rooted in the same pool-pinning pattern.\n\n    Mitigation: do the DB-bound search inside the request session,\n    explicitly ``await db.close()`` to return the connection to the\n    pool, then call ``summarize_memories`` (the no-DB LLM helper from\n    PR #228). ``AsyncSession.close()`` is idempotent, so FastAPI's\n    dependency cleanup at request end runs harmlessly.\n    \"\"\"\n    # Read endpoint — readable set widening applies (see /search).\n    auth.enforce_readable_tenant(body.tenant_id)\n    if auth.tenant_id:\n        if body.filter_agent_id:\n            fleet_id_hint = body.fleet_ids[0] if body.fleet_ids and len(body.fleet_ids) == 1 else None\n            _agent = await get_or_create_agent(db, body.tenant_id, body.filter_agent_id, fleet_id_hint)\n            if not body.fleet_ids and _agent.get(\"fleet_id\") and _agent.get(\"trust_level\", 0) < 2:\n                body.fleet_ids = [_agent[\"fleet_id\"]]\n            if body.fleet_ids and len(body.fleet_ids) == 1:\n                await enforce_fleet_read(db, body.tenant_id, body.filter_agent_id, body.fleet_ids[0])\n        await check_and_increment(db, body.tenant_id, \"search\")\n\n    from core_api.services.memory_service import search_memories\n    from core_api.services.organization_settings import resolve_config\n    from core_api.services.recall_service import summarize_memories\n\n    t0 = time.perf_counter()\n\n    # ── Phase 1: DB-bound — config + search ──────────────────────\n    config = await resolve_config(db, body.tenant_id)\n    memories = await search_memories(\n        db,\n        tenant_id=body.tenant_id,\n        query=body.query,\n        fleet_ids=body.fleet_ids,\n        filter_agent_id=body.filter_agent_id,\n        caller_agent_id=body.filter_agent_id,\n        memory_type_filter=body.memory_type_filter,\n        status_filter=body.status_filter,\n        top_k=body.top_k,\n        valid_at=body.valid_at,\n        recall_boost=config.recall_boost,\n        graph_expand=config.graph_expand,\n        tenant_config=config,\n        readable_tenant_ids=auth.readable_tenant_ids if auth.is_cross_tenant_read else None,\n    )\n\n    # Release the pooled DB connection before the LLM round-trip.\n    # FastAPI's outer ``get_db`` ``async with`` will re-close on exit —\n    # idempotent, so it's a no-op there.\n    await db.close()\n\n    # ── Phase 2: LLM brief (no DB held) ──────────────────────────\n    return await summarize_memories(\n        memories,\n        body.query,\n        config,\n        valid_at=body.valid_at,\n        top_k=body.top_k,\n        t0=t0,\n    )\n\n\n# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n# Redistribute\n# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n\n@router.post(\"/memories/redistribute\", response_model=RedistributeResponse)\nasync def redistribute_memories(\n    body: RedistributeRequest,\n    tenant_id: str = Query(...),\n    agent_id: str = Query(..., description=\"Requesting agent (must be trust_level >= 3)\"),\n    auth: AuthContext = Depends(get_auth_context),\n    db: AsyncSession = Depends(get_db),\n):\n    \"\"\"Bulk-reassign memories to a different agent.\n\n    Admin-only (trust_level >= 3).  Moves memories to ``target_agent_id``,\n    auto-promoting ``scope_agent`` → ``scope_team`` to prevent data loss.","lineStart":1380,"lineEnd":1749,"totalLines":2023,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/routes/memories.py","time":{"start":1780728479791,"end":1780728479801}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0864e1f84848cb91016a23c291e29c819191546ab0b4551cbf"}},"id":"prt_e9bb04006001so6Usqwfansd48","sessionID":"ses_164517a81ffemKHCVyXGgLqE5C","messageID":"msg_e9baf2985001z0btwIoqxLOoa9"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780728480059,"sessionID":"ses_164517a81ffemKHCVyXGgLqE5C","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_ZYseQaJ2CUYBFxoAkNbnEDx7","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/recall_service.py","offset":1,"limit":260},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/recall_service.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: \"\"\"Recall service: search + LLM summarization into a concise context paragraph.\"\"\"\n2: \n3: import json as _json\n4: import logging\n5: import time\n6: from datetime import UTC, datetime\n7: \n8: from sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import AsyncSession\n9: \n10: from core_api.constants import (\n11:     DEFAULT_SEARCH_TOP_K,\n12:     MEMORY_RECALL_SUMMARY_MAX_TOKENS,\n13:     MEMORY_RECALL_SUMMARY_TEMPERATURE,\n14: )\n15: from core_api.providers._retry import call_with_fallback\n16: from core_api.services.memory_service import search_memories\n17: \n18: logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n19: \n20: RECALL_PROMPT = \"\"\"\\\n21: I will give you several facts and observations from past interactions and ingested content. \\\n22: Please answer the question based on the relevant facts. Answer the question step by step: \\\n23: first extract all the relevant information, then reason over the information to get the answer.\n24: \n25: When the question requires combining facts from different memories, trace the connection \\\n26: explicitly. Pay attention to dates within the facts — events described in past tense \\\n27: occurred before the date the memory was recorded.\n28: \n29: Grounding rules — follow strictly:\n30: - Quote only text that appears verbatim in the memories below.\n31: - Do not invent identifiers, field names, dates, titles, or numbers. If a detail is not \\\n32: present in the memories, do not include it.\n33: - If the memories do not contain enough information to answer, say so plainly. Do not \\\n34: infer beyond the evidence.\n35: \n36: Memories:\n37: \n38: {memories}\n39: \n40: {reference_date_line}Question: {query}\n41: Answer (step by step):\"\"\"\n42: \n43: \n44: def _format_memories_for_prompt(memories: list) -> str:\n45:     \"\"\"Format memories as a JSON array for structured LLM consumption.\n46: \n47:     Only fields that exist on the API response are exposed. No ordinal IDs, no\n48:     renamed schema fields — the model must not be able to cite identifiers or\n49:     field names that a caller cannot resolve.\n50:     \"\"\"\n51:     items = []\n52:     for m in memories:\n53:         item: dict = {\"type\": m.memory_type}\n54:         if m.title:\n55:             item[\"title\"] = m.title\n56:         if m.status and m.status != \"active\":\n57:             item[\"status\"] = m.status\n58:         content = m.content or \"\"\n59:         ts = getattr(m, \"ts_valid_start\", None)\n60:         if ts:\n61:             date_str = ts[:10] if isinstance(ts, str) else ts.strftime(\"%Y-%m-%d\")\n62:             content = f\"[{date_str}] {content}\" if content else f\"[{date_str}]\"\n63:         item[\"content\"] = content or None\n64:         items.append(item)\n65:     return _json.dumps(items, indent=2, ensure_ascii=False)\n66: \n67: \n68: async def summarize_memories(\n69:     memories: list,\n70:     query: str,\n71:     config,\n72:     *,\n73:     valid_at: datetime | None = None,\n74:     diagnostic: bool = False,\n75:     diagnostic_ctx: dict | None = None,\n76:     top_k: int = DEFAULT_SEARCH_TOP_K,\n77:     t0: float | None = None,\n78: ) -> dict:\n79:     \"\"\"LLM-only summarization step. No DB access.\n80: \n81:     Audit finding P3: ``memclaw_recall`` previously held the\n82:     ``_mcp_session()`` open across the multi-second LLM round-trip,\n83:     pinning a pooled DB connection. This helper takes already-fetched\n84:     memories + the resolved tenant config and produces the same dict\n85:     shape the legacy ``recall()`` wrapper returned, so the MCP tool can\n86:     exit the session block before invoking it.\n87: \n88:     ``t0`` is the caller's ``time.perf_counter()`` checkpoint for the\n89:     surrounding handler — passing it preserves the original \"recall_ms\n90:     measures end-to-end from auth-pass\" semantics. Omitted callers get\n91:     a fresh checkpoint that only times the summary itself.\n92:     \"\"\"\n93:     if t0 is None:\n94:         t0 = time.perf_counter()\n95:     diagnostic_ctx = diagnostic_ctx or {}\n96: \n97:     if not memories:\n98:         resp = {\n99:             \"query\": query,\n100:             \"summary\": \"No relevant context found.\",\n101:             \"memory_count\": 0,\n102:             # C4 — ``items`` aliases ``memories`` so consumers that\n103:             # pattern-match on /search's shape don't silently get zero\n104:             # results when hitting /recall instead. Both keys point at\n105:             # the same list (here trivially empty).\n106:             \"memories\": [],\n107:             \"items\": [],\n108:             \"recall_ms\": int((time.perf_counter() - t0) * 1000),\n109:         }\n110:         if diagnostic:\n111:             resp[\"diagnostic\"] = {\n112:                 \"recall_prompt\": None,\n113:                 \"recall_model\": None,\n114:                 \"recall_provider\": None,\n115:                 \"all_candidates\": diagnostic_ctx.get(\"all_candidates\", []),\n116:                 \"top_k_used\": top_k,\n117:                 \"retrieval_strategy\": diagnostic_ctx.get(\"retrieval_strategy\"),\n118:                 \"search_params\": {\n119:                     k: (float(v) if isinstance(v, (int, float)) else v)\n120:                     for k, v in diagnostic_ctx.get(\"search_params\", {}).items()\n121:                 },\n122:             }\n123:         return resp\n124: \n125:     # Sort chronologically so the LLM sees a natural timeline. Callers\n126:     # may have already sorted; the operation is idempotent.\n127:     _DT_MIN_UTC = datetime.min.replace(tzinfo=UTC)\n128:     memories.sort(key=lambda m: getattr(m, \"ts_valid_start\", None) or _DT_MIN_UTC)\n129: \n130:     memories_text = _format_memories_for_prompt(memories)\n131:     if valid_at:\n132:         reference_date_line = f\"Current Date: {valid_at.strftime('%Y-%m-%d')}\\n\"\n133:     else:\n134:         reference_date_line = \"\"\n135: \n136:     provider = config.recall_provider\n137: \n138:     if not config.recall_enabled:\n139:         # C4 — materialise once; alias under both ``memories`` and\n140:         # ``items`` keys so consumers built against /search's shape see\n141:         # the same list.\n142:         _memories_dumps = [m.model_dump(mode=\"json\") for m in memories]\n143:         resp = {\n144:             \"query\": query,\n145:             \"summary\": \"Recall summarization is disabled.\",\n146:             \"memory_count\": len(memories),\n147:             \"memories\": _memories_dumps,\n148:             \"items\": _memories_dumps,\n149:             \"recall_ms\": int((time.perf_counter() - t0) * 1000),\n150:         }\n151:         if diagnostic:\n152:             resp[\"diagnostic\"] = {\n153:                 \"recall_prompt\": None,\n154:                 \"recall_model\": None,\n155:                 \"recall_provider\": provider,\n156:                 \"all_candidates\": diagnostic_ctx.get(\"all_candidates\", []),\n157:                 \"top_k_used\": top_k,\n158:                 \"retrieval_strategy\": diagnostic_ctx.get(\"retrieval_strategy\"),\n159:                 \"search_params\": {\n160:                     k: (float(v) if isinstance(v, (int, float)) else v)\n161:                     for k, v in diagnostic_ctx.get(\"search_params\", {}).items()\n162:                 },\n163:             }\n164:         return resp\n165: \n166:     prompt = RECALL_PROMPT.format(\n167:         query=query, memories=memories_text, reference_date_line=reference_date_line\n168:     )\n169: \n170:     def _fake_recall() -> str:\n171:         \"\"\"No-LLM fallback: join top memory contents.\"\"\"\n172:         return \" \".join(m.content[:100] for m in memories[:3])\n173: \n174:     async def _do_recall(llm) -> str:\n175:         return await llm.complete_text(\n176:             prompt,\n177:             temperature=MEMORY_RECALL_SUMMARY_TEMPERATURE,\n178:             max_tokens=MEMORY_RECALL_SUMMARY_MAX_TOKENS,\n179:         )\n180: \n181:     recall_model = getattr(config, \"recall_model\", None)\n182:     summary = await call_with_fallback(\n183:         primary_provider_name=provider,\n184:         call_fn=_do_recall,\n185:         fake_fn=_fake_recall,\n186:         tenant_config=config,\n187:         service_label=\"recall\",\n188:         model_override=recall_model,\n189:         timeout=30.0,\n190:     )\n191: \n192:     recall_ms = int((time.perf_counter() - t0) * 1000)\n193: \n194:     # C4 — materialise once; alias under both ``memories`` and ``items``.\n195:     _memories_dumps = [m.model_dump(mode=\"json\") for m in memories]\n196:     result = {\n197:         \"query\": query,\n198:         \"summary\": summary,\n199:         \"memory_count\": len(memories),\n200:         \"memories\": _memories_dumps,\n201:         \"items\": _memories_dumps,\n202:         \"recall_ms\": recall_ms,\n203:     }\n204: \n205:     if diagnostic:\n206:         result[\"diagnostic\"] = {\n207:             \"recall_prompt\": prompt,\n208:             \"recall_model\": recall_model or \"default\",\n209:             \"recall_provider\": provider,\n210:             \"all_candidates\": diagnostic_ctx.get(\"all_candidates\", []),\n211:             \"top_k_used\": top_k,\n212:             \"retrieval_strategy\": diagnostic_ctx.get(\"retrieval_strategy\"),\n213:             \"search_params\": {\n214:                 k: (float(v) if isinstance(v, (int, float)) else v)\n215:                 for k, v in diagnostic_ctx.get(\"search_params\", {}).items()\n216:             },\n217:         }\n218: \n219:     return result\n220: \n221: \n222: async def recall(\n223:     db: AsyncSession,\n224:     tenant_id: str,\n225:     query: str,\n226:     fleet_ids: list[str] | None = None,\n227:     filter_agent_id: str | None = None,\n228:     caller_agent_id: str | None = None,\n229:     memory_type_filter: str | None = None,\n230:     status_filter: str | None = None,\n231:     top_k: int = DEFAULT_SEARCH_TOP_K,\n232:     valid_at: datetime | None = None,\n233:     diagnostic: bool = False,\n234:     readable_tenant_ids: list[str] | None = None,\n235: ) -> dict:\n236:     \"\"\"Search memories and synthesize a context summary.\n237: \n238:     Returns: {\"query\": ..., \"summary\": ..., \"memory_count\": ..., \"memories\": [...], \"items\": [...], \"recall_ms\": ...}\n239: \n240:     ``memories`` and ``items`` both reference the same list — the ``items``\n241:     alias was added by C4 so consumers built against ``/search``'s\n242:     response shape (which keys on ``items``) don't silently get zero\n243:     results when hitting ``/recall``.\n244: \n245:     Thin wrapper over ``search_memories`` + ``summarize_memories``. MCP\n246:     tool callers that already hold the search results and tenant config\n247:     should invoke ``summarize_memories`` directly so they can close\n248:     their DB session before the LLM round-trip (audit P3). This wrapper\n249:     is retained for the REST surface and other callers that prefer the\n250:     one-shot ergonomics.\n251:     \"\"\"\n252:     t0 = time.perf_counter()\n253: \n254:     from core_api.services.organization_settings import resolve_config\n255: \n256:     config = await resolve_config(db, tenant_id)\n257:     diagnostic_ctx: dict = {} if diagnostic else {}\n258:     memories = await search_memories(\n259:         db,\n260:         tenant_id=tenant_id,\n\n(Showing lines 1-260 of 285. Use offset=261 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\"\"\"Recall service: search + LLM summarization into a concise context paragraph.\"\"\"\n\nimport json as _json\nimport logging\nimport time\nfrom datetime import UTC, datetime\n\nfrom sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import AsyncSession\n\nfrom core_api.constants import (\n    DEFAULT_SEARCH_TOP_K,\n    MEMORY_RECALL_SUMMARY_MAX_TOKENS,\n    MEMORY_RECALL_SUMMARY_TEMPERATURE,\n)\nfrom core_api.providers._retry import call_with_fallback\nfrom core_api.services.memory_service import search_memories\n\nlogger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n\nRECALL_PROMPT = \"\"\"\\","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/recall_service.py","text":"\"\"\"Recall service: search + LLM summarization into a concise context paragraph.\"\"\"\n\nimport json as _json\nimport logging\nimport time\nfrom datetime import UTC, datetime\n\nfrom sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import AsyncSession\n\nfrom core_api.constants import (\n    DEFAULT_SEARCH_TOP_K,\n    MEMORY_RECALL_SUMMARY_MAX_TOKENS,\n    MEMORY_RECALL_SUMMARY_TEMPERATURE,\n)\nfrom core_api.providers._retry import call_with_fallback\nfrom core_api.services.memory_service import search_memories\n\nlogger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n\nRECALL_PROMPT = \"\"\"\\\nI will give you several facts and observations from past interactions and ingested content. \\\nPlease answer the question based on the relevant facts. Answer the question step by step: \\\nfirst extract all the relevant information, then reason over the information to get the answer.\n\nWhen the question requires combining facts from different memories, trace the connection \\\nexplicitly. Pay attention to dates within the facts — events described in past tense \\\noccurred before the date the memory was recorded.\n\nGrounding rules — follow strictly:\n- Quote only text that appears verbatim in the memories below.\n- Do not invent identifiers, field names, dates, titles, or numbers. If a detail is not \\\npresent in the memories, do not include it.\n- If the memories do not contain enough information to answer, say so plainly. Do not \\\ninfer beyond the evidence.\n\nMemories:\n\n{memories}\n\n{reference_date_line}Question: {query}\nAnswer (step by step):\"\"\"\n\n\ndef _format_memories_for_prompt(memories: list) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Format memories as a JSON array for structured LLM consumption.\n\n    Only fields that exist on the API response are exposed. No ordinal IDs, no\n    renamed schema fields — the model must not be able to cite identifiers or\n    field names that a caller cannot resolve.\n    \"\"\"\n    items = []\n    for m in memories:\n        item: dict = {\"type\": m.memory_type}\n        if m.title:\n            item[\"title\"] = m.title\n        if m.status and m.status != \"active\":\n            item[\"status\"] = m.status\n        content = m.content or \"\"\n        ts = getattr(m, \"ts_valid_start\", None)\n        if ts:\n            date_str = ts[:10] if isinstance(ts, str) else ts.strftime(\"%Y-%m-%d\")\n            content = f\"[{date_str}] {content}\" if content else f\"[{date_str}]\"\n        item[\"content\"] = content or None\n        items.append(item)\n    return _json.dumps(items, indent=2, ensure_ascii=False)\n\n\nasync def summarize_memories(\n    memories: list,\n    query: str,\n    config,\n    *,\n    valid_at: datetime | None = None,\n    diagnostic: bool = False,\n    diagnostic_ctx: dict | None = None,\n    top_k: int = DEFAULT_SEARCH_TOP_K,\n    t0: float | None = None,\n) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"LLM-only summarization step. No DB access.\n\n    Audit finding P3: ``memclaw_recall`` previously held the\n    ``_mcp_session()`` open across the multi-second LLM round-trip,\n    pinning a pooled DB connection. This helper takes already-fetched\n    memories + the resolved tenant config and produces the same dict\n    shape the legacy ``recall()`` wrapper returned, so the MCP tool can\n    exit the session block before invoking it.\n\n    ``t0`` is the caller's ``time.perf_counter()`` checkpoint for the\n    surrounding handler — passing it preserves the original \"recall_ms\n    measures end-to-end from auth-pass\" semantics. Omitted callers get\n    a fresh checkpoint that only times the summary itself.\n    \"\"\"\n    if t0 is None:\n        t0 = time.perf_counter()\n    diagnostic_ctx = diagnostic_ctx or {}\n\n    if not memories:\n        resp = {\n            \"query\": query,\n            \"summary\": \"No relevant context found.\",\n            \"memory_count\": 0,\n            # C4 — ``items`` aliases ``memories`` so consumers that\n            # pattern-match on /search's shape don't silently get zero\n            # results when hitting /recall instead. Both keys point at\n            # the same list (here trivially empty).\n            \"memories\": [],\n            \"items\": [],\n            \"recall_ms\": int((time.perf_counter() - t0) * 1000),\n        }\n        if diagnostic:\n            resp[\"diagnostic\"] = {\n                \"recall_prompt\": None,\n                \"recall_model\": None,\n                \"recall_provider\": None,\n                \"all_candidates\": diagnostic_ctx.get(\"all_candidates\", []),\n                \"top_k_used\": top_k,\n                \"retrieval_strategy\": diagnostic_ctx.get(\"retrieval_strategy\"),\n                \"search_params\": {\n                    k: (float(v) if isinstance(v, (int, float)) else v)\n                    for k, v in diagnostic_ctx.get(\"search_params\", {}).items()\n                },\n            }\n        return resp\n\n    # Sort chronologically so the LLM sees a natural timeline. Callers\n    # may have already sorted; the operation is idempotent.\n    _DT_MIN_UTC = datetime.min.replace(tzinfo=UTC)\n    memories.sort(key=lambda m: getattr(m, \"ts_valid_start\", None) or _DT_MIN_UTC)\n\n    memories_text = _format_memories_for_prompt(memories)\n    if valid_at:\n        reference_date_line = f\"Current Date: {valid_at.strftime('%Y-%m-%d')}\\n\"\n    else:\n        reference_date_line = \"\"\n\n    provider = config.recall_provider\n\n    if not config.recall_enabled:\n        # C4 — materialise once; alias under both ``memories`` and\n        # ``items`` keys so consumers built against /search's shape see\n        # the same list.\n        _memories_dumps = [m.model_dump(mode=\"json\") for m in memories]\n        resp = {\n            \"query\": query,\n            \"summary\": \"Recall summarization is disabled.\",\n            \"memory_count\": len(memories),\n            \"memories\": _memories_dumps,\n            \"items\": _memories_dumps,\n            \"recall_ms\": int((time.perf_counter() - t0) * 1000),\n        }\n        if diagnostic:\n            resp[\"diagnostic\"] = {\n                \"recall_prompt\": None,\n                \"recall_model\": None,\n                \"recall_provider\": provider,\n                \"all_candidates\": diagnostic_ctx.get(\"all_candidates\", []),\n                \"top_k_used\": top_k,\n                \"retrieval_strategy\": diagnostic_ctx.get(\"retrieval_strategy\"),\n                \"search_params\": {\n                    k: (float(v) if isinstance(v, (int, float)) else v)\n                    for k, v in diagnostic_ctx.get(\"search_params\", {}).items()\n                },\n            }\n        return resp\n\n    prompt = RECALL_PROMPT.format(\n        query=query, memories=memories_text, reference_date_line=reference_date_line\n    )\n\n    def _fake_recall() -> str:\n        \"\"\"No-LLM fallback: join top memory contents.\"\"\"\n        return \" \".join(m.content[:100] for m in memories[:3])\n\n    async def _do_recall(llm) -> str:\n        return await llm.complete_text(\n            prompt,\n            temperature=MEMORY_RECALL_SUMMARY_TEMPERATURE,\n            max_tokens=MEMORY_RECALL_SUMMARY_MAX_TOKENS,\n        )\n\n    recall_model = getattr(config, \"recall_model\", None)\n    summary = await call_with_fallback(\n        primary_provider_name=provider,\n        call_fn=_do_recall,\n        fake_fn=_fake_recall,\n        tenant_config=config,\n        service_label=\"recall\",\n        model_override=recall_model,\n        timeout=30.0,\n    )\n\n    recall_ms = int((time.perf_counter() - t0) * 1000)\n\n    # C4 — materialise once; alias under both ``memories`` and ``items``.\n    _memories_dumps = [m.model_dump(mode=\"json\") for m in memories]\n    result = {\n        \"query\": query,\n        \"summary\": summary,\n        \"memory_count\": len(memories),\n        \"memories\": _memories_dumps,\n        \"items\": _memories_dumps,\n        \"recall_ms\": recall_ms,\n    }\n\n    if diagnostic:\n        result[\"diagnostic\"] = {\n            \"recall_prompt\": prompt,\n            \"recall_model\": recall_model or \"default\",\n            \"recall_provider\": provider,\n            \"all_candidates\": diagnostic_ctx.get(\"all_candidates\", []),\n            \"top_k_used\": top_k,\n            \"retrieval_strategy\": diagnostic_ctx.get(\"retrieval_strategy\"),\n            \"search_params\": {\n                k: (float(v) if isinstance(v, (int, float)) else v)\n                for k, v in diagnostic_ctx.get(\"search_params\", {}).items()\n            },\n        }\n\n    return result\n\n\nasync def recall(\n    db: AsyncSession,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    query: str,\n    fleet_ids: list[str] | None = None,\n    filter_agent_id: str | None = None,\n    caller_agent_id: str | None = None,\n    memory_type_filter: str | None = None,\n    status_filter: str | None = None,\n    top_k: int = DEFAULT_SEARCH_TOP_K,\n    valid_at: datetime | None = None,\n    diagnostic: bool = False,\n    readable_tenant_ids: list[str] | None = None,\n) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Search memories and synthesize a context summary.\n\n    Returns: {\"query\": ..., \"summary\": ..., \"memory_count\": ..., \"memories\": [...], \"items\": [...], \"recall_ms\": ...}\n\n    ``memories`` and ``items`` both reference the same list — the ``items``\n    alias was added by C4 so consumers built against ``/search``'s\n    response shape (which keys on ``items``) don't silently get zero\n    results when hitting ``/recall``.\n\n    Thin wrapper over ``search_memories`` + ``summarize_memories``. MCP\n    tool callers that already hold the search results and tenant config\n    should invoke ``summarize_memories`` directly so they can close\n    their DB session before the LLM round-trip (audit P3). This wrapper\n    is retained for the REST surface and other callers that prefer the\n    one-shot ergonomics.\n    \"\"\"\n    t0 = time.perf_counter()\n\n    from core_api.services.organization_settings import resolve_config\n\n    config = await resolve_config(db, tenant_id)\n    diagnostic_ctx: dict = {} if diagnostic else {}\n    memories = await search_memories(\n        db,\n        tenant_id=tenant_id,","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":260,"totalLines":285,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/recall_service.py","time":{"start":1780728480051,"end":1780728480058}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0864e1f84848cb91016a23c291e2a881919ed100881f20b918"}},"id":"prt_e9bb040c1001cMOyIslwy42ToS","sessionID":"ses_164517a81ffemKHCVyXGgLqE5C","messageID":"msg_e9baf2985001z0btwIoqxLOoa9"}}
